commit_message:
Fixes an get_volume_stats reporting issue

This patch fixes a bug introduced in the last get_volume_stats
patch that caused the method to fail.  I Also added another set
of unit tests to catch any future issues related to get_volume_stats.

Fixes Bug: #1178418

Cherry picked from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/28722

Change-Id: I5901057b2edb07f14706e23e81e75aa7567a127a

commit_message:
Remove service.model_disconnected

It appears this code is never used anywhere and was the reason for a try
'except Exception' block in servicegroup.  This 'except Exception' block
may be hiding critical bugs.

Change-Id: Ie071b141867acd74f2a02a9616b0f9874c13434b
Related-Bug: #1221987

[{'created': '2013-09-19 20:41:58.000000000', 'message': 'Adding RBD data striping capabilities to OpenStack (python-cinderclient)

blueprint rbd-stripe-parameters

When creating an RBD volume, various command line options can be specified;

two of these relate to data striping and are stripe_count and stripe_unit.

stripe_count: specifies the number of objects to stripe over before looping back to the first object.
stripe_unit: specifies the stripe unit size in bytes

We modify python-cinderclient to pass the RBD stripe parameters from Horizon to Cinder

This modification to cinderclient/v1/volumes.py simply receives the stripe_count
and stripe_unit parameters from Horizon via the VolumeManager.create method
and allows them to be used by Cinder

This implementation requires:
Adding RBD data striping capabilities to OpenStack (Horizon)
Adding RBD data striping capabilities to OpenStack (Cinder)

Change-Id: I8d985fc8d498544a2cf275e0cff77488ca3788b9

commit_message:
Adding RBD data striping capabilities to OpenStack

The python-cinderclient implementation

When creating an RBD volume, various command line options can be specified;

two of these relate to data striping and are stripe_count and stripe_unit.

stripe_count: specifies the number of objects to stripe over before looping back to the first object.
stripe_unit: specifies the stripe unit size in bytes

We modify python-cinderclient to pass the RBD stripe parameters from Horizon to Cinder

This modification to cinderclient/{v1|v2}/volumes.py simply receives the stripe_count
and stripe_unit parameters from Horizon via the VolumeManager.create method
and allows them to be used by Cinder

This implementation requires:
Adding RBD data striping capabilities to OpenStack (Horizon)
Adding RBD data striping capabilities to OpenStack (Cinder)

blueprint rbd-stripe-parameters

Change-Id: I8d985fc8d498544a2cf275e0cff77488ca3788b9

Sorry, guys, still not sure how we can avoid a queue backing up.'}, {'account_id': 2828, 'date': '2013-09-18 22:18:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-09-18 22:27:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

@portante:

In the abstract, there's nothing in here that will prevent someone from calling ThreadPool.background() arbitrarily many times as fast as they can, and thus filling the queue.

However, when you look at the call site for ThreadPool.background(), you can see that the prior statement is a call to ThreadPool.force_run_in_thread(). Thus, there's no request that makes only background/async calls without also making run_in_thread/sync calls, and therefore the queue depth is bounded.

If there were something that only made background/async calls and never made a run_in_thread/sync call, then yes, that hypothetical thing could cause the queue to grow without bound. However, we don't have anything like that in Swift.

@redbo:

Thanks for fixing up that test."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-18 22:48:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

Can we reduce how often we need to issue this cleanup by just checking on open when it is likely we'll need the cleanup?"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-09-19 06:37:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

An interesting question about the relative speed of these sorts of things. Fortunately, we have benchmarks. :)

https://gist.github.com/smerritt/6619709

tl;dr: a listdir of a small directory from buffercache is about 17x slower than enqueuing and dequeuing a thing in a Queue.Queue.

Now, clearly hash_cleanup_listdir() will be at least that slow; there's a very good chance it'll have to do some unlinking, too. If the upload takes long enough to complete, then the directory listing is likely to no longer be in buffercache, so the listdir will have to hit disk again.

I'm not saying there are no possible improvements to be made here; obviously, doing nothing is faster than doing something. However, given the relative speeds of filesystem operations and in-memory queues, I'm happy with this as-is.

(Well, almost happy. -1 because pep8 has a complaint, but that's just some nitpicking reified into a python program and given authority by Jenkins (I, for one, welcome our robot-linter overlords))"}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-09-19 06:58:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

@protante & @sam - you're benchmarking the wrong thing :P

Until someone can verify or refute these runs I'd like to hold off on merging this - it may be nothing, but it got me nervous.

http://paste.openstack.org/show/47289/

In an effort to understand the failure conditions I wanted to see "how bad is it when shit goes off the rails" - I added a big 'ol time.sleep inside the diskfile's hash_cleanup_listdir.

My thought was that on threads_per_disk and a *little* sleep I should get better throughput with PUTs and DELETEs than tpool.  Which meh, need more testing to be sure - maybe.

And with a *lot* of sleep I should fill up all my pools and probably even timeout/blowup (or at least introduce enough congestion to see things slow down) - but instead my object server stopped responding entirely.

After the benchmark I couldn't even HEAD objects.  It would just hang (in accept?)

I know a 10 second sleep is silly, but with a slow disk there's bound to be a multi-second hash_cleanup_listdir somewhere at some point right?  How slow does it have to be for this to wind up like this - why did it break down?  Can it recover?  Is it just something in my environment?  my ssbench run?  Bad tuning?

If anyone thinks this is a completely unreasonable failure mode I'd be curious why - or even more so a set of tests that they feel show that even on a busy system backgrounding things won't cause any issue.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-09-19 22:59:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Move obj datadir cleanup to background thread

Add a .background() method to thread pools.  It queues up code to be ran in a
thread, then forgets about it.

Then use the new method to run datadir cleanup asynchronously, since it isn't
necessary for correctness and it might perceptibly speed up DELETEs and PUTs
that overwrite.  It might also imperceptibly speed up other PUTs and POSTs.

I'm not sure this is a good idea, so feel free to criticize.

(Nobody liked the idea of moving all of finalize_put to the background.
Bunch of scaredy cats.  We have 3 servers, it'll work somewhere.)

Change-Id: I755c80b0ce303fb948234df643e4e3bd7c9aca9b

commit_message:
Updated the section-dashboard-access.xml file

Updated the dashboard access section to include new screenshots
for the Admin and Project tabs and also the new options available to
users in the Havana release.
Removed the old dashboard-project.png and dashboard_admin_overview.png images.

Change-Id: Ida3cc07a2d0f4cba1aee559597352ebf97461c61

commit_message:
Fix misused assertTrue in unit tests

Refactored unit tests to use assertEqual instead of assertTrue
where needed.

Fixes bug #1226374

Change-Id: I678b2e7fcc522c8776c7fc0a554c1fc229ab781e

commit_message:
VMware: fix bug for incorrect cluster access

For a number of methods only the first cluster would be accessed
and not the correct cluster.

Fixes bug: 1226211

Change-Id: I4eb3c360fc81de172e46418d5a16dd2bd7077fea

[{'created': '2013-09-26 04:40:51.000000000', 'message': 'Fake true return value for git show --quiet

Upstream change [1] introduced --quiet to the git show command.
Unfortunately on older git's before [2], to quote the git change-log:

    ...allows us to catch the "--quiet" option which causes some of the
    log-related commands to misbehave as it would otherwise get passed on
    to the diff.

Misbehaviour includes returning 1 instead of 0, which breaks the
stack.sh run.  Thus we fake a return value to be maximally compatible

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48011/

'}]
commit_message:
Fake true return value for git show --quiet

Upstream change [1] introduced --quiet to the git show command.
Unfortunately on older git's before [2], to quote the git change-log:

    ...allows us to catch the "--quiet" option which causes some of the
    log-related commands to misbehave as it would otherwise get passed on
    to the diff.

Misbehaviour includes returning 1 instead of 0, which breaks the
stack.sh run.  Thus we fake a return value to be maximally compatible

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48011/
[2] https://github.com/git/git/commit/1c40c36b9acbb55726ea0fcf98714a85e159e45f

Change-Id: I6f06899133ffe377b948a9a491b29c2a13bbd01a

commit_message:
Allow -P to be invoked multiple times

If --parameters is specified more than once it is assumed
that each one contains only one parameter key=value.

This means semicolons are ignored if there is more than one -P
specified.

This should be fully backwared compatible, a single -P will
be assumed to be semicolon delimited.

Change-Id: Ic202ff3e0596b786cd5b07c53509f97a95d41585
Closes-Bug: #1224825
Closes-Bug: #1229030

commit_message:
Add an option for always synchronizing status

This patch adds an option for always synchronizing operational status
on a show operation; regardless of the synchronization thread, when
this option is enabled, the resource status is always fetched from
the backend.

The patch also fixes an issue observed when running test_nvp_sync
alone.

Bug #1229149
Bug #1229243

Change-Id: Ifef52ac1c48e32f413d51fc04fd926073335665d

commit_message:
Ensure router exists when auto_schedule_routers

Currently, the auto_schedule_routers() accepts parameter router_ids,
which may contain invalid router ids, since we've already filtered
them via plugin.get_routers(), we can directly use that safe object.

Closes-Bug: #1217998
Closes-Bug: #1210877

Change-Id: I6196f16cca65fee4e848173d0a0a10fde967195d

commit_message:
Ensure get_all_flavors returns deleted items

When a flavor is deleted a new one may be created with the same name.
However when calling flavors.get_all_flavors(inactive=True) only the
latest flavor with the same name is returned. When inactive=True all
flavors should be returned regardless of their name or replacement
state.

Change the key used in the returned dictionary from
flavors.get_all_flavors() to the flavorid rather than the name. This
allows multiple flavors with the same name to be returned.

Fixes bug 1215295
Change-Id: I1b0c93b3e12714a5c0798aa87c9e3fe9bc14519a

commit_message:
Sync rootwrap with code from oslo

The rootwrap module had been directly edited in commit 1d366293.
These are all minor changes bringing neutron up to commit c03f247

c03f247 Skip hidden files while traversion rootwrap filters
3f4d1d5 Fix os.getlogin() problem with no tty
fc04531 Send rootwrap exit error message to stderr
3663010 rootwrap: improve Python 3 compatibility
28395d9 Fixes files with wrong bitmode

Fixes bug #1229492

Change-Id: Ica406e021700578b27c3337498011059c3a78719

commit_message:
Enable tenant isolation to tempest for neutron

This commit re-enables tenant isolation in tempest for neutron. This
is a requirement for running tempest in parallel. This commit depends
on tempest change I7587c85017cca09f7a67eae0670f67b2bceacb60

Fixes bug 1216076

Change-Id: I63a30bacd48cecd110fb90e1fc718249c2b1904b

commit_message:
Do not translate HOT param constraints

Do not translate HOT parameter constraint definitions and have them processed
by default CFN-based code. Instead, do HOT parameter constraint validation in
HOTParamSchema class to handle HOT-specific constraint syntax appropriately.
This is more robust than trying to map the new HOT syntax to old CFN
constraint style.

This patch is cleanup and first in a row for fixing the use of HOT templates
as provider templates.

Partial-Bug: #1224111

Change-Id: Ia35f281f874b906aabeb684fd9caca03dd994b9c

commit_message:
Rename counter_name to meter_name in alarm

In the newest ceilometer alarm version counter_name property was renamed to
meter_name. Right now heat uses old ceilometer client which still support
counter_name but newest ceilometer backend does not.

Change-Id: Ie7876119dc9b2a80d862f10de5f7265ad2a059f0
Closes-Bug: #1222830

[{'created': '2013-09-20 23:04:28.000000000', 'message': "Fixing database instance launch workflow

Two fixes related to one broken workflow.

First, 1227918 is a lack of support for trove backends that don't
have volume support enabled. To fix this, the user can now enter
into 0 for the volume size to work around this.  This alters how
the value is passed troveclient. Working with trove team to get a
programmatic way to determine is volume support is enabled.

Second, 1228416 is broken javascript when trying to launch a
database instance due to a couple of factors. The template for the
help is mislinked to use the project/instance one. Two, the fields
in the flavor that trove returns are different than the fields that
nova returns for flavor. This causes an exception when trying to
generate the quota/usage graphs on the right hand side of the form.
Since the javascript is looking for hardcoded values, this is not a
trivial fix so the offensive code has been removed until it can be
revisited. Additionally, there is no guarantee that the nova backend
trove uses is the same as the one regular compute uses. Needs more
thought/work.

Combined bug fixes because they are closely related to the same
action.

Change-Id: Ia378896d1d52067ac136c55ece9b527f44dd646b
Closes-bug: #1227918
Closes-bug: #1228416

commit_message:
Fixing database instance launch workflow

Two fixes related to one broken workflow.

First, 1227918 is a lack of support for trove backends that don't
have volume support enabled. To fix this, the user can now enter
into 0 for the volume size to work around this.  This alters how
the value is passed troveclient. Working with trove team to get a
programmatic way to determine is volume support is enabled.

Second, 1228416 is broken javascript when trying to launch a
database instance due to a couple of factors. The template for the
help is mislinked to use the project/instance one. Two, the fields
in the flavor that trove returns are different than the fields that
nova returns for flavor. This causes an exception when trying to
generate the quota/usage graphs on the right hand side of the form.
Since the javascript is looking for hardcoded values, this is not a
trivial fix so the offensive code has been removed until it can be
revisited. Additionally, there is no guarantee that the nova backend
trove uses is the same as the one regular compute uses. Needs more
thought/work.

Combined bug fixes because they are closely related to the same
action.

Change-Id: Ia378896d1d52067ac136c55ece9b527f44dd646b
Closes-bug: #1227918
Closes-bug: #1228416

'}, {'account_id': 5162, 'date': '2013-09-18 18:44:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

The shared firewall use case is not fully implemented yet, but shared firewall policies and rules are, at least based on some of the testing I have done. This patch only addresses policies and rules.'}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2013-09-20 03:15:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Salvatore, the intention here is to fix the sharing of the firewall_policy and firewall_rules which is independent of the sharing of the firewall. Yes, we are not attempting sharing of firewalls in Havana.

The expectation is that this fix will allow a tenant who is recognized with the role of creating rules and policies to create them, audit them, and make them visible to other tenants who can then associate them with their firewalls and use them.

Without this fix, the tenant which creates the firewall will have to create the rules and policies, and thus audit workflow is never exercised.'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-09-25 14:57:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

I get the point on sharing of rules.

I have a pedant nit on tests - perhaps if we want unit tests to validate default policies in policy.json we might put those tests in a separate test case.'}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2013-09-26 03:33:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: No score

commit_message:
Allow sharing of firewall rules and policies in policy.json

Updated policy for firewall_policy and firewall_rule to allow sharing
among tenants. Added a new firewall sharing rule to enable this.

Change-Id: I5d4d9f94fb3abffe4d1b03c46fd5b13a8a4a4f09
Fixes: bug #1217103

[{'created': '2013-09-09 19:52:53.000000000', 'message': "DRAFT of bind9 cleanup

My first attempt at the bind9 plugin, lots of things wrong with it
but I wanted to get some feedback. I've included a better
explanation in the designate/backend/impl_bind9.py file.
Just let me know what you think. Thanks! Hopefully I do this
draft review right.

Change-Id: I474ac1c2f0f1b5d8027862ac372bad653cb5d7ea
"}, {'created': '2013-09-17 17:42:07.000000000', 'message': "BIND9 Plugin Cleanup

General cleanup of the bind9 plugin. Adds rndc addzone/delzone
functionality, which speeds up the plugin by allowing for dynamic
syncing of zones. Removes management of central bind configuration

commit_message:
BIND9 Plugin Cleanup

General cleanup of the bind9 plugin. Adds rndc addzone/delzone
functionality, which speeds up the plugin by allowing for dynamic
syncing of zones. Removes management of central bind configuration
from designate copying bind's statement of zones over. Also
updates some documentation to reflect the change.

Change-Id: I474ac1c2f0f1b5d8027862ac372bad653cb5d7ea

commit_message:
Change response code for successful delete image member to 204.

The delete image member call currently returns 200 with no response
body.  According to the API contract, 200 means to expect a body.
This patch changes the response code to 204.

Change-Id: Id48187b3c47e39075a352d3027dd3d3451d46905
Closes-Bug: #1229366

If we are going to refactor the database connection strings, I think we should go even further.

1. I would like to be able to pass the parts of the connection string instead of the database_connection string. In general, users only have to update the db_host and db_password, everything else should be able to assume defaults. In this case, database_connection would default to false or undef, and be used to override the individual components when supplied.

2.  I don't think the database_connection belongs in init.pp as it is no longer required for all components (at least not for the compute component)"}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-09-12 20:10:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: No score

Dan Bode: I think we need to be careful in our refactoring though. What Ian has done here still lines up perfectly with the upstream config files.

If we go and split things out into username/password/host, etc I think we could get into trouble with some database type/formats (perhaps non-SQL types) which may not use all of these options.

To me it seems better to just follow a model where our configuration clearly maps to the service config file.'}, {'account_id': 7156, 'date': '2013-09-12 22:57:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

I agree with Dan. Such fine grain control over each values should be reserved for an higher abstraction layer such as puppet-openstack or an other similar module/tool.

Unless OpenStack itself implements such configuration granularity, we are better not doing it. I fear a maintenance nightmare we don't want."}, {'account_id': 2265, 'date': '2013-09-12 23:57:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

for some additional context, my desire to for these more granular settings comes from an attempt to write a higher level tool focused on understanding how configured data elements populate class parameters.

commit_message:
Deprecate sql_* for database_*

Upstream change d5ae9ea70ed878e08e1d195f34c1989ecdd0b74f deprecated
default sql_* options for a new [database] section.

This deprecates the sql_ options and moves the new options into
the [database] sub-section of the config file.  If sql_* values are
given, they should be used but give a deprecation warning.

Change-Id: I05db83ace63399c0b2ebd63f74f5dc76ff5d3e9a

[{'created': '2013-09-26 19:14:30.000000000', 'message': "Do not set tenant description in cache

Prevously, after the full list of tenants
was retrieved to build the cache, an
extra call was made to tenant-get per tenant to
retrieve the tenant's description.

This extra call changed the cache creation
operation from O(1) to O(N).

This commit improves the query complexity to
0(1) by moving the description lookup from
part of self.instances to the description
getter method (essentailly making it lazy).

This will work different depending on if you
are interacting with the resource in query
vs. manage mode.

In query mode, self.instances will build
out the cache withouth the description initially.
Since description is a properly, it will invoke
the getter method.

In manage mode, the description getter will only be invoked
for cases where the description is managed.

Partial-Bug: 1224179
Change-Id: Id9268678e122ba3aa3e5b0bcfd77466071a4192d
(cherry picked from commit b48032a42fd2019d0d11e1dafa22fd8431b0c1c9)
"}]
commit_message:
Do not set tenant description in cache

Prevously, after the full list of tenants
was retrieved to build the cache, an
extra call was made to tenant-get per tenant to
retrieve the tenant's description.

This extra call changed the cache creation
operation from O(1) to O(N).

This commit improves the query complexity to
0(1) by moving the description lookup from
part of self.instances to the description
getter method (essentailly making it lazy).

This will work different depending on if you
are interacting with the resource in query
vs. manage mode.

In query mode, self.instances will build
out the cache withouth the description initially.
Since description is a properly, it will invoke
the getter method.

In manage mode, the description getter will only be invoked
for cases where the description is managed.

Partial-Bug: 1224179
Change-Id: Id9268678e122ba3aa3e5b0bcfd77466071a4192d
(cherry picked from commit b48032a42fd2019d0d11e1dafa22fd8431b0c1c9)

commit_message:
Make tenant name lookup for keystone user lazy

Previously, when you managed a keystone user, Puppet
would start by loading all information available
about each user. Most of this information was loaded
with a single call to user-list, but the tenant name
required an additional two commands (one to get the
tenantId, and an additional one to get the tenant name)

This patch makes the tenant lookup lazy, meaning that
those additional calls will only be performed when
the tenant attribute is actually used. This will
cause a significant performance increase for the
case where only a large set of users exists, and
only a small fraction of them need to be managed.

Partial-Bug: 1224179
Change-Id: I7141d8e922005ecae33c2c596c9806a03fede53f
(cherry picked from commit c194f374e2c54d03f34f28f002e478b8556c94c3)

commit_message:
Do not set tenant description in cache

Prevously, after the full list of tenants
was retrieved to build the cache, an
extra call was made to tenant-get per tenant to
retrieve the tenant's description.

This extra call changed the cache creation
operation from O(1) to O(N).

This commit improves the query complexity to
0(1) by moving the description lookup from
part of self.instances to the description
getter method (essentailly making it lazy).

This will work different depending on if you
are interacting with the resource in query
vs. manage mode.

In query mode, self.instances will build
out the cache withouth the description initially.
Since description is a properly, it will invoke
the getter method.

In manage mode, the description getter will only be invoked
for cases where the description is managed.

Partial-Bug: 1224179
Change-Id: Id9268678e122ba3aa3e5b0bcfd77466071a4192d

commit_message:
fix tee errors

Do not specify /dev/fd3 directly, use >&3 instead. This change enables
to use stack.sh as an upstart script, and with VERBOSE=False, it will
print the expected messages.

Fixes bug 1230342

Change-Id: I6e3a81fd435e8c46d553bfdee08f8bf42d0f4387

We landed a fix to bump the nova default rate limits. As such
we should be able to drop this sleep command.

commit_message:
Bug#1192017-Added user quota info for Compute.

Added procedures for managing user quota info in Compute.
Updated the procedure for setting default quotas (to match the
manpage;'default' moved to end of command). Updated displayed tables,
and updated the listing of quota name/descriptions to match. Also
updated the title of the networking quotas page to be consistent with
other sections.
Updated dashboard page: added note about tenant user updates, combined
compute and block storage tables, removed floating and fixed ip descriptions
(were removed from dashboard listing), fixed procedures to match
Havana 3 changes.

Closes-Bug: #1192017

Change-Id: I059b1bbd6792be2fadfb28f49c2b2b3ec89e1d28

commit_message:
Allow enabling Neutron orchestrated PXE.

This is off by default for compatibility with older Neutron's, but we
need it to get rid of file injection. As we want to support Havana
too, we probably need to be able to run both with and without this, so
making it an option seems reasonable.

Change-Id: If29d1e38930975b763bb9d10b37fb3ae040da96d

Add native ipmi driver

Implemented a power driver for baremetal node that uses the native
python ipmi driver called pyghmi.

Change-Id: I41954ebba7c8fa2873a7f1a1f73a4511b0afa301
Implements: blueprint native-ipmi

Integer types support in api

This patch adds validation 'driver_info' (for nodes)
and 'extra' (nodes, chassis, ports) for accept
integers as values.

commit_message:
Split v1/shell.py into different files

Splitting v1/shell.py into one file per resource makes the code more
organized and in the long run helps to improve code readability.

Change-Id: Ia57019548158ffe33a1eca444405107caa327936

(9 inline comments)

Overall, I really like the move to sphinx.

A couple of comments about the patch set that seems to apply to several files.  I started to leave some inline comments, but there are some recurring themes, so I'll just list them here:

- Can we keep the switch from github.com to git.openstack.org isolated to the other review request for that?  If this patch depends on that, can we mark it as such?

- devtest.md is going away, yet scripts/extra-docs still creates devtest.md from devtest.sh.  Doesn't this need an update as well, to create the new devtest.rst instead?

- boot-seed-vm and README.md also need updates to no longer reference devtest.md

- In devtest.rst, there are several indentation issues where lines are not indented when they should be.  This causes the instructions list to reset it's ordering back to 1 each time.  In general, the footnotes section does not look correct at all from an indentation perspective, at least that is case for the html docs, which is what I generated. 

- I'd like to see a reference somewhere on how to generate the docs, e.g. "python setup.py build_sphinx".'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2013-09-22 19:19:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Work In Progress

could some one help me understand this bug;

If I am not wrong, even with max_stacks_per_tenant limit, DOS attack is possible because tenant can create and delete  multiple stacks (within the limit) in parallel and that could result in DOS attack...correct? should we solve this problem by limiting number of concurrent stack requests from a tenant?'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-09-19 21:03:49.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-09-19 21:15:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Vijender, thanks for thinking this through and asking a great question. You are right that this will not entirely prevent a DOS of a size larger than the limit.

If a single tenant submits > $limit stack creations all at once, they will have a window right before the engine stores the stack which reaches $limit, for any other in-flight stack creation requests to be popped off the queue and have the query run, finding $limit - 1 stacks, thus allowing continuing to some pushing beyond the limit. However, as soon as that stack is stored, all subsequent create requests will fail until all of those extra stacks are deleted.

Given that the engine is only I/O-concurent (via eventlet), and there is very little I/O going on between the create request starting and the store bit, I don't believe the risk is high enough to warrant an attempt for a global limit on single-tenant concurrency. We can also recommend pushing the concurrency limits back to the API at layer 7 which is a well known operational pattern for HTTP API's."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-09-19 21:19:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (2 inline comments)

commit_message:
Add config option to limit max stacks per tenant

Tenants will not be able to create more than max_stacks_per_tenant top
level stacks. This should prevent any one tenant from being able to
exhaust a Heat engine's resources.

Fixes bug #1221849

Change-Id: I29be4ecf5d5b9eb44d7ecc01907d08f30ac27990

commit_message:
Do not merge test of neutron tenant isolation.

This is just a test of neutron tenant isolation. It hard codes
the tenant_isolation config variable to True.

Change-Id: Ic3e79f913cdb034851b01fc8e2890f0f2eabb65e

commit_message:
Allow keystone to run from apache

Provide a template for running keystone as a mod_wsgi process and enable
it from configuration.

Based on: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/36474/
Also-by: zhang-hare <zhuadl@cn.ibm.com>
Implements: blueprint devstack-setup-apache-keystone

Change-Id: Icc9d7ddfa4a488c08816ff4ae0b53c0134a1016b

commit_message:
Use ovs-vsctl instead of brctl for debug output.

Fixes an issue in the get_state_from_host function where
brctl would fail (because we don't install it).

Change-Id: I99427d71dda8e789c0211bb8948b936c306da937

commit_message:
Sync config group case with upstream.

Neutron now uses lower case for most config file groupings.

This change syncs with upstream so that the correct config
file case is used for the various OVS and linuxbridge components.

Change-Id: I1a471505b48161b9ee6bbe2a28db82c96a8c2598

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-08 18:53:30.000000000', 'message': "Handling network resources in tenant isolation

Functionality is added to create and delete isolated network, subnet and router
when isolated credentials are created and deleted for a primary, admin or alt
tenant.

When a set of isolated credentials are created, the tenant gets also a private
network, subnet and router. The router connects the tenat's network to the
public network designated by public_network_id in etc/tempest.conf

Change-Id: I7587c85017cca09f7a67eae0670f67b2bceacb60
Fixes: bug #1216076
"}, {'created': '2013-09-08 21:28:29.000000000', 'message': "Handling network resources in tenant isolation

Functionality is added to create and delete isolated network, subnet and router
when isolated credentials are created and deleted for a primary, admin or alt
tenant.

When a set of isolated credentials are created, the tenant gets also a private
network, subnet and router. The router connects the tenat's network to the

commit_message:
Handling network resources in tenant isolation

Functionality is added to create and delete isolated network, subnet and router
when isolated credentials are created and deleted for a primary, admin or alt
tenant.

When a set of isolated credentials are created, the tenant gets also a private
network, subnet and router. The router connects the tenat's network to the
public network designated by public_network_id in etc/tempest.conf

Change-Id: I7587c85017cca09f7a67eae0670f67b2bceacb60
Fixes: bug #1216076

commit_message:
Handled ajax request crash after session timeout

process_response refers request.horizon in case of ajax
request, but this attribute was not set on session timeout.
redirection to previous page was not sent.

IMPORTANT NOTE:
After a session timeout, when logging back in the requested modal dialogue
is displayed in a static view page.

Change-Id: I793b1c0a4c51107d263de0fe144dca26f5216d7a
Closes-Bug: #1214812

commit_message:
perf(mongodb): Combine project and queue message fields

This patch merges the message and queue collections' project name and
queue name fields into a single 'p_q' field, named to denote the
compound nature of the scoped queue name string.

This should reduce index complexity, making for faster inserts and
finds. This hypothesis obviously needs to be verified during the
review process for this patch.

Change-Id: I3da09806ad50c2d79f1f0c03bee68f1cc4ee787d
Implements: blueprint api-perf-tuning

subject: fix(mongodb): Marker generation creates a bottleneck under heavy load

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-18 22:44:41.000000000', 'message': "fix(mongodb): Marker generation creates a bottleneck under heavy load

This patch changes markers so that they are generated using a per-queue
side counter. A heuristic is used to mitigate a race condition. Due to the
new semantics, partial inserts are no longer possible due to collisions,
which ended up simplifying the retry logic for posting messages.

As a consequence of this patch, the last message posted no longer needs
to remain in the queue indefinitely, rendering marconi-gc unnecessary,
and so it has been removed.

Also, since the mongod GC worker runs once a minute, the queries no longer
filter out expired-but-not-yet-gc'd messages; on average, a message may
live more than 30 seconds passed it's expected lifetime, but I do not
think that this will harm or complicate any application building on top of
Marconi, practically speaking. That being said, it is worth calling out
in documentation.

Closes-Bug: #1218602
Change-Id: I34e24e7dd7c4e017c84eb5929ce37ad4c9e5266a

commit_message:
fix(mongodb): Marker generation creates a bottleneck under heavy load

This patch changes markers so that they are generated using a per-queue
side counter. A heuristic is used to mitigate a race condition. Due to the
new semantics, partial inserts are no longer possible due to collisions,
which ended up simplifying the retry logic for posting messages.

As a consequence of this patch, the last message posted no longer needs
to remain in the queue indefinitely, rendering marconi-gc unnecessary,
and so it has been removed.

Also, since the mongod GC worker runs once a minute, the queries no longer
filter out expired-but-not-yet-gc'd messages; on average, a message may
live more than 30 seconds passed it's expected lifetime, but I do not
think that this will harm or complicate any application building on top of
Marconi, practically speaking. That being said, it is worth calling out
in documentation.

Closes-Bug: #1218602
Change-Id: I34e24e7dd7c4e017c84eb5929ce37ad4c9e5266a

commit_message:
Fix "personality" parameter for binary contents

We can specify the decoded binary contents as the "personality"
parameter of "Create a server" API since the following commit:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/20977/

So "text only" of contents is not necessary now.

Change-Id: Ib4d67b77529b00eb3f2bc4d0d036f1efbaf78b00

commit_message:
Remove _get_compute_info from filter_scheduler.py

After patch I6de33ada6dc377e20f8df07da92244f2c150b9fe and
Ie6f104368140b69a60e124ea96ef6bf7715fe34e, in filter_scheduler.py,
_get_compute_info has no use and no one is calling it, so we
can remove it directly.

Fix bug 1228475

Change-Id: Ia85068e402b6f0b2a9ed2a809d1c1dc63e0f3041

Update man page version

date to the Havana release date (Oct 17 -
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Havana_Release_Schedule ).

(1 inline comment)

Spelling nit in the commit message."}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2013-08-22 14:00:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2013-08-22 14:00:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2013-08-22 14:01:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

New patchset patch-id matches previous patchset, but commit message has changed.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-08-22 14:45:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Nothing against this patch per se, but specifying a 'global' vnc password for all VM's sounds wrong to say the least; should that be auto-generated and sent back to the client and VM's spawn time? Do we want to go ahead with the current practice?"}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2013-08-23 06:11:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Armando: at the moment there was a global VNC password. If the password was not set then the user would be unable to access the VM via VNC. The fix enables the user to access the VNC without password access (similar to KVM).
I agree that moving forwards we can provide a VNC password for each VM. I like that idea. But that is a different feature.'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2013-08-23 14:43:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

recheck no bug'}, {'account_id': 7400, 'date': '2013-08-23 15:29:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Much better than the default password I had tried to get in.  I'm assuming the vnc client likes the missing password better than the '' password with the default security type."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-23 15:50:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

(1 inline comment)

Consider:
   vnc_pass = CONF.vmware.vnc_password or 'password'

Rationale:

Building on Dan Smith's comments...

The use of a global cloud-wide VNC password is not good practice. In fact, it is so bad practice it should be disabled. If the ESX host can't deal with a password, it should not present the illusion that a password can provide cloud-wide security.

Better to propose a change that allows some form of strong encryption between the proxy and the VNC host."}, {'account_id': 7400, 'date': '2013-08-23 17:05:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
VMware: enable VNC access without user having to enter password

When the vnc_password was not configured in the 'vmware' section
the user was unable to access the VNC console. The user would be
requested to enter a password but all attempts would fail.

The 'vnc_password' was added as a workaround to the problem above.

The fix ensures that the VMware driver behaves like all of the other
virt drivers when it comes to the VNC access, that is, the user will
not have to enter a password.

The password support will be deprecated and removed in the next
version.

Fixes bug: 1215352

Change-Id: I728861b8965ee3d3b8444a0440ddd0a8e5bb9021

Fix Tester cleanup crashes rally execution

Fixes bug 1231338

commit_message:
Add example with return values in API v2 docs

Add a "real" example of a groupby statistics query with return
values in API v2 documentation.

The example is taken from an actual query run on a machine
running Devstack and Ceilometer.

Addresses bug # 1228465

commit_message:
Add host os type for connector

Host os type is needed for some cinder storage drivers,
so nova should send this msg to cinder when attaching
volume to instance.
This patch make cinder identify:
Linux, Windows, XenServer and Vmware ESX

fixes bug 1224578
Change-Id: Ib21f7fa6ca082a465a69bfc0f62db51ee5aadad8

commit_message:
Ensure nullable=False for netid in packetfilters table

From the initial commit of NEC plugin, network_id of packetfilters
table is nullable=False, but in folsom_initial db migration script
nullable is set to True. This commit ensure nullable=False for
network_id in packetfilters table in any migration revision.

Change-Id: I2f1ebc16b57d8d6548255079c66d326d97fda5b6
Closes-Bug: #1229508

commit_message:
Remove CinderVolume id attribute

Using the id attribute can result in problems when validating a
template, as the resource_id is empty at that point, so we remove it to
prevent issues, as people ought to use Ref anyway.

Closes-Bug: #1230140
Change-Id: I16778d8036e7e2ccacf93caa4581ae0b0368b7c2

commit_message:
api ec2token: allow auth_uri conf to be set via keystone_authtoken

We already require the keystone_authtoken heat.conf section for the
auth_token middleware, and heat_keystoneclient.py.  So this patch
allows us to reuse the auth_uri specified in that section instead
of requiring a duplicate auth_uri to be specified in [ec2authtoken]

Change-Id: Ic5efafb7743aeddca990a4c560b423293108e1e0
Closes-Bug: #1229674

commit_message:
Update sample config generator script

This patch reverts 13d80020. The help message should be added
in oslo-incubator since generate_sample.sh is synced from there also.

Resolves bug #1204204

9f2b93b Sample config file generator clean up
33f9f78 Replaces relative path to absolute path in conf file generator
c97e17b Refactors if statement in config generator
8b11fda Provide useful defaults for config generator
4c02e0a Unset OS_xx variable before generate configuration

Change-Id: I96fcb39c0c620c147fea5c96416e506a758619ce

commit_message:
Force textmode consoles on baremetal

Physical hardware often has console interception hardware for OOB
monitoring/management. Prevent the kernel from switching into a
graphical console mode so the hardware can do its job.

Change-Id: I3a5b17ab194238ada34fee1c834de22fbdcd7430
Related-Bug: #1178112

commit_message:
fix: age presented as negative

Adds unit tests to verify that the bug never appears again. The unit
test is effective for storage backends that use timeutils to measure
the age of a message.

Bug manifests itself in both claims and messages.

Change-Id: I7fec4533236df5b232c0500835ac8e1d9d261d09
Closes-Bug: 1229358

commit_message:
Update tox.ini to use new features

tox 1.6 allows us to skip the sdist step, which is slow. This does that.
It also allows us to override the install line. In this case, it's
important as it allows us to stop getting pre-release software we
weren't asking for.

Change-Id: I2641c847403f61c5da8a8be0c8804c7c23a043ed

commit_message:
Change hard coded numbers to constants in security group tests

Security groups tests in Neutron contain a lot of hard coded HTTP return codes
and protocol numbers. These should be changed to use constants.

Change-Id: Ibecff3821c54f12848a05648f35381a0c73a0896
Fixes: Bug 1218928

[{'created': '2013-09-25 19:20:29.000000000', 'message': 'Fix subparsers add_parser() regression

With SubCommandOpt, the handler() callback gets invoked with a
subparsers object which has a add_parser() method. The arguments to
this method match the arguments to the ArgumentParser constructor and
the arguments are passed to the class for our ArgumentParser instance.

However, we added a ArgumentParser subclass (_CachedArgumentParser) so
that we could sort the output of --help ... but the subclass doesn't
support all the arguments of the parent class.

glance-control is the only known example of a SubCommandOpt user which
passes unusual arguments to subparsers.add_parser(). It uses the parent
arg and blows up at startup with:

   File "./bin/glance-control", line 276, in add_command_parsers
     parser = subparsers.add_parser(server, parents=[cmd_parser])
   File "/usr/lib64/python2.7/argparse.py", line 1064, in add_parser
     parser = self._parser_class(**kwargs)
 TypeError: __init__() got an unexpected keyword argument 'parents'

It appears we broke glance-control back in June (commit 2951391), but
nobody noticed it until 1.2.0 was released and broke stable/grizzly
because we stopped using glance-control in the Havana glance unit tests
before this regression.

Closes-Bug: #1230416
Change-Id: I8d1b52e5390295726eb49af32eb7cab14c29592c
'}]
commit_message:
Fix subparsers add_parser() regression

With SubCommandOpt, the handler() callback gets invoked with a
subparsers object which has a add_parser() method. The arguments to
this method match the arguments to the ArgumentParser constructor and
the arguments are passed to the class for our ArgumentParser instance.

However, we added a ArgumentParser subclass (_CachedArgumentParser) so
that we could sort the output of --help ... but the subclass doesn't
support all the arguments of the parent class.

glance-control is the only known example of a SubCommandOpt user which
passes unusual arguments to subparsers.add_parser(). It uses the parent
arg and blows up at startup with:

   File "./bin/glance-control", line 276, in add_command_parsers
     parser = subparsers.add_parser(server, parents=[cmd_parser])
   File "/usr/lib64/python2.7/argparse.py", line 1064, in add_parser
     parser = self._parser_class(**kwargs)
 TypeError: __init__() got an unexpected keyword argument 'parents'

It appears we broke glance-control back in June (commit 2951391), but
nobody noticed it until 1.2.0 was released and broke stable/grizzly
because we stopped using glance-control in the Havana glance unit tests
before this regression.

Closes-Bug: #1230416
Change-Id: I8d1b52e5390295726eb49af32eb7cab14c29592c

commit_message:
Fix problem with never stopping stress tests

This fix will fix the issue for never stopping stress test in
the nightly build jobs. It changes three problems related to this:

 - An exception in tearDown() will not cause a endless loop
 - Hanging processes will be killed with -9 after a while
 - tox job will stop on first error

Fixes-bug: 1230357
Change-Id: I3a0160295d98fdc7f8ffce64cc4a08c5c8ae654a

CloudBase-Init service starts faster.

CloudBase-Init launch moved to first boot script which starts without delay.

Fixes: MRN-492

commit_message:
Default tenant id for quota_defaults.

For now manila quota_defaults can't be called without
explisit specificaton of tenant id. To fix this issue
shell py was modified with changes for
do_quota_defaults that implemets default value for
tenant id.

Change-Id: Ic44929f7941d1fb8c6626295853f56f8a561215b

commit_message:
Fix VCDriver to pick the datastore that has capacity

Changed to remove the hardcoding of selecting the first
datastore, instead the instance disk requirement is
calculated and the appropriate datastore is selected.

fix bug #1171930

Change-Id: I7857557d02cb56c45d52c6fc4bd956fc9180e836

commit_message:
Remove DHCP_DRIVER from the seed boot call.

The seed doesn't need variation at this point, and config.json is
painful to edit. Rather than adding more sed debt, I think we can
avoid parameterising the seed for boot-technology for now, and just
migrate it entirely once the neutron native PXE is stable.
Pure Havana can support Neutron native PXE - it just won't be able
to support no-file-injection etc.

Change-Id: I92d203c5e496ca5d688243c50dbc140f8cc238a4

[{'created': '2013-09-25 12:16:15.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Update Ceilometer alembic requirement to 0.6.0 version"

This reverts commit 0b3819b4a58dde35f8446ac3f76ecf8aa04c25ef.

This change was originally motivated entirely by usage of the new 'type_'
kwarg in calls to op.drop_constraint() from two ceilometer migration scripts,
even though the old 'type' form was retained for backward compatability:

  https://alembic.readthedocs.org/en/latest/ops.html

  "Changed in version 0.5.0: The type parameter is now named type_.
  The old name type will remain for backwards compatibility."

To avoid needlessly imposing the alembic 6.0 on distros for which this
version is not yet packaged, I propose to revert these migrations to use
the older form in ceilometer:

  https://review.openstack.org/48069

The global requirement may be similiarly reverted.

Change-Id: I71d5ca9aaf4789817ca2e0cf3f90a6ef8b63acd1
'}]
commit_message:
Revert "Update Ceilometer alembic requirement to 0.6.0 version"

This reverts commit 0b3819b4a58dde35f8446ac3f76ecf8aa04c25ef.

This change was originally motivated entirely by usage of the new 'type_'
kwarg in calls to op.drop_constraint() from two ceilometer migration scripts,
even though the old 'type' form was retained for backward compatability:

  https://alembic.readthedocs.org/en/latest/ops.html

  "Changed in version 0.5.0: The type parameter is now named type_.
  The old name type will remain for backwards compatibility."

To avoid needlessly imposing the alembic 6.0 on distros for which this
version is not yet packaged, I propose to revert these migrations to use
the older form in ceilometer:

  https://review.openstack.org/48069

The global requirement may be similiarly reverted.

Change-Id: I71d5ca9aaf4789817ca2e0cf3f90a6ef8b63acd1

commit_message:
Log object lazy-loads

This is a trivial change that will be extremely helpful in tracking
down spurious lazy-loads and performance issues in the field. Simply
log to DEBUG any time we do a lazy-load of something. In practice,
this should be relatively rare.

Change-Id: I5e7bc058ba5ad17536a361367a0def5c4953643e

commit_message:
attach/detach_volume() take instance as a parameter

Previously the methods take instance['name'] as a parameter.
With this change, ComputeDriver can lookup informations about
the instance from hypervisor (in bare-metal driver, it is a local DB)
by any other attributes of the instance.

blueprint general-bare-metal-provisioning-framework

Change-Id: Ibd0567f34ed5053909ce1a408f9cbf87516ba597

commit_message:
Add hosts to pcloud.

Adding a new api to provision a reserved host to a plcoud.
A reserved host is one that  belongs to an aggregate named
"pcloud:reserve". Work in progress.

Partially implements blueprint: whole-host-allocation

Change-Id: I08230a2aaa3ba01465abe4e2a6624f2abd0ad7e9

commit_message:
Let apache module manage Listen directives

Without this change, the content of file /etc/apache2/ports.conf was flapping
between 'Listen 80' and 'Listen 0.0.0.0:80' at each puppet agent run.

(/Stage[main]/Apache/Concat[/etc/apache2/ports.conf]/File[/etc/apache2/ports.conf]/content) content changed '{md5}63840008875259fe2f00c2160146bde2' to '{md5}ac3b658e433eba85f350d4068b0ef826'
(/Stage[main]/Horizon/File_line[httpd_listen_on_bind_address_80]/ensure) created

Change-Id: I259cc013c14376a119f18eb1c0df7f35ad3a7cf1

[{'created': '2013-08-24 11:21:59.000000000', 'message': 'Implement pagination support in driver backends

This patch builds on the support for filtering in the driver
backends to also provide pagination.  For drivers that are unable
to paginate, this will still be done at the controller level.

Limitations:

commit_message:
Implement pagination support in driver backends

This patch builds on the support for filtering in the driver
backends to also provide pagination.  For drivers that are unable
to paginate, this will still be done at the controller level.

If the caller does not request pagination (by omitting 'page' from
the query string), then no pagination is attempted and the collection
results will be unchanged.

Limitations:

- LDAP pagination is not yet supported in the driver, and is currently
  still handled at the controller level. This will be provded by a
  separate patch.

DocImpact

Implements bp pagination-backend-support

Change-Id: I129acf59f09ba08e6a551368d0b06803a90cb158

In python 3 print operator is not supported, so we should
use only print() functions.

In cases when we should change ouptut source or print multiple elements
(e.g. print >> sys.out, "something" or print 1,2,3)
We should use from __future__ import print_function

Aslo in this patch some usage of locals() is clean up.

Change-Id: I9e591debdde0492104651443cbbdd90189f4628e
'}]
commit_message:
Use print() func instead of print operator

In python 3 print operator is not supported, so we should
use only print() functions.

In cases when we should change ouptut source or print multiple elements
(e.g. print >> sys.out, "something" or print 1,2,3)
We should use from __future__ import print_function

Aslo in this patch some usage of locals() is clean up.

Change-Id: I9e591debdde0492104651443cbbdd90189f4628e

commit_message:
handle KeyError in api: GET 'os-hypervisors/detail'

* using dict.get('key', 'default') to handle it.
* also fix same issue in v3 api

Change-Id: Ic80a1e6d487e68ae7afbf28b126aab2b866a7ed7
Closes-Bug: #1221679

Maybe that changed when we weren't caching account_info in the request environment.  Maybe it just made sense since collecting account_info wasn't ever going to change the behavior of any known auth system and it just limited the surface area for bugs. OTOH, this might make the intent and purpose of delay_denial pretty murky at this point?  Maybe there's only limited value in calling authorize before collecting all the info? @gholt ok, so removing early bailout from all the container and half the account methods isn't really a problem.

"The delay_denial procedures allow skipping possibly expensive access control string retrievals for requests that can be approved without that information, such as administrator or account owner requests."

That is to say @delay_denail "allows" *swift* to decide when *it* thinks your authorize method needs more info.

A)
"Should this request be allowed?"
"No."
"Well... let's just wait and see anyway"

B)
"Should this request be allowed?"
"Well... probably?  Based on this information, I'm going to say... YES!"
"Ok sweet, well I'm going to go get the acl's now anyway - but i'm definitely not talking to you again."

So this change would remove tempauth's ability to reject a container PUT without collecting account_info - which might make a 403 a little slower, or waste some cache space; but if a client was just *trying* to make swift call get_info more it could always just move the request one level deeper.  I don't think that's a problem.  Am I missing something?

@davidhadas - what's the deal with pass_through_headers?

@Clay 

1. Thanks for the review. 

2. The current auth system do not seem to require changes in auth systems that are do not use account ACLs. It does delay_denial for container post/put/delete and for account get/head, but after the 'delay' the same response denial response is sent as before to the client. Auth systems that decide to use account ACLs, will get a chance to do so, but those that does not, will still deny the same requests as before. So it may not be needed to disable this feature by yet another config param. 

3. The entire auth system is under tested. We do need to work on adding tests to the auth system. Yet this need does not seem to be related to this specific patch. To overcome that need as you noted, we did some extra testing using curl scripts.

4. It may be a new direction to consider adding new functional tests with curl. This looks like a great way to test the entire API very quickly and with little code. Maybe we wrap curl with a python object making it even easier (and friendlier to python coders). I will put some thought into this after the current rush time is over. 

Bottom line, if someone sees a need to add yet another config param to disable this option given that it will not change the behavior of its system besides making calls that should be rejected, rejected after delay instead of of instantly, we can easily do so. Else, I suggest to merge as is for 1.9.

K these tests are great.  I've decided I totally prefer the expansion of denial to practically every method vs. refactoring request authorization in this change.  I still think this is a totally needed feature and I'm happy with the implementation.

I'm still like +1.5, because I'm scared how other folks are going to feel about perserving behavior with alternative auth middleware.

I spun up my devstack/keystone instance and not surprisingly I could set 'X-Account-Read' - but it had no effect.  Which is better than broken; or allowing unauthorized access - so maybe that's good enough?

Generally I'd like to argue we should try to evolve our strategy on "perserve default behavior" a little bit so that when we have something that is new, additive, and almost certainly better you don't have to know to change some secret config var to get the coolness in the new version (think SLO or object-server threadpool) - but I know that's a sensitive topic; and authorization is probably not the firmest ground for me to try and make that argument.

Besides, I think it's totally reasonable to say you don't need to allow setting X-Account-Read/Write unless you have a middleware in the pipeline that supports it.  So,  I think AccountController's pass_through_headers should maybe be empty by default, and middleware that needs it (e.g. TempAuth) can optionally enable/disable it by monkey_patching on __init__ or calling some classmethod?

On the other extreme you make it a config var then you have to remember to add CoolMiddlewareWithAccountACLs *and* enable the secret can_haz_cool_feature in the proxy conf.  Gag.

Whatever it is needs to be documented.  I'm open to better ideas?

Or if someone wants to come along as say "I agree; I don't care if you can *set* X-Account-Read: r:* in Keystone as long as it doesn't do anything bad".  Then I'll quickly change my +1.5 to a +2 and welcome this awesome new feature :D'}, {'account_id': 866, 'date': '2013-06-26 04:36:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: (2 inline comments)

This patch set adds hiding of the TempURL keys 

TempURL middleware now filters such keys for anyone but the true account owner. Such that users with access to the account metadata (via read access on the account ACLs) would not be able to see such keys. 

Users that have access to the account via account ACLs are called account_owner='vice' while users that are the true owners have account_owner=True as before. 

For backward compatibility with auth systems that do not set account_owner, if no account owner was defined, it is assumed that account ACLs are not supported and therefore the behaviour is kept unchanged and  no filtering of keys is done by the TempURL middleware.

Note that I did not yet examine if we have proper tests to cover the area that was changed."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-06-27 15:06:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13: Doesn't seem to work

I added a callback mechanism to the controllers which could make our code simpler in middleware. 

      resp = controller_callback(req, resp)

This is offered as an alternative to hooking start_response which has several limitations - as well demonstrated in the Swift Middleware today. 

In this callback we provide the middleware with the req and resp as parameters, which enables the middleware to easily extend core swift behaviour post request handling while it may have access to the env that was used to form the request as well as the full response as calculated by core swift. The middleware may modify the response as appropriate and return the modified response. 

This is more powerful than hooking start_response (in which we have no env, req or resp but only the status and the headers of the response. This mechanism also does not require mingling with the body iterable (as we do today in some Swift Middleware) which would allow us to make some current middleware hooks simpler.'}, {'account_id': 1216, 'date': '2013-06-28 15:30:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

Can you split off the callback functionality into its own review? And make any other changes not directly related into split offs as well (I don't know that there are any more, but just in case)."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-06-28 15:39:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: Works for me

Account in swift is an overloaded word. It means a user sometimes and sometimes it means the aggregate of containers. 

Account ACLs allow a user to access a "aggregate of containers" belonging to someone else. 

When we use account to refer to the "aggregate of containers" - it is confusing to also use it to refer to a user.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-07-10 09:43:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

@Christian

I'd like x_remove_headers method too; but personally I think we can fix it later and merge w/o because you can set acl's to the empty string (you can't do that with curl mind you; but only because it wouldn't send headers with empty values, other clients will)

@David

Can you look of these tests and tell me if they make sense to you?

http://paste.openstack.org/show/39920/

Personally I think it still feels clunky.

With all the work you did to cache the account_info in the environ, it's seems pretty cheap to call get_info in the proxy.controller.obj methods and add account_acl - it seems like your tempauth code will already do the right thing:

http://paste.openstack.org/show/39921/

^ could use some tests

Final thoughts,

I don't love the new auth middleware contract, in addition to:

1) acl
2) swift_owner

you've added:

3) account_acl
4) account_write_acl (only set on container READ?)
5) swift_writer

But frankly it works and I'm not sure I have purposed any better options (or any other core??? Anyone??? Hello???)  :P

Maybe just a new attribute "acls" which is a dict that maps 'account_read_acl', 'acccount_write_acl', 'container_read_acl', and 'container_write_acl'?  And legacy middleware can continue to have the same context sensitive behavior for container acl until it's phased out in some indeterminate future?  I think getting the API right here is key, we're going to have to live with it for awhile.

OTOH, This plus python-swiftclient commit c460ebf is sorta totally awesome.  I think I could live with this.  Maybe I'm just getting worn out, but I feel like I'm having trouble remembering what Tim Peter's said after "Now is better than never."

I'm going to +1 this again hoping to get some other eyes on it and in the meantime keep poking at it, I think there may still be some tactical stuff, docs and nits that needs to be polished up.'}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2013-07-18 13:25:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 21: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

+1 from me, let's add the x-remove-* part later.

Additionally, I'd really like this to see in Swift.

For example, one could create an account and grant several people with own accounts access to this account. This is useful if you want your users to have own private accounts and an shared, common account for group work."}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2013-07-29 19:10:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2013-08-08 22:42:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21: (4 inline comments)

I agree quite a bit with the comments Clay left.


I think the weirdest part of this feature is the change in the auth system contract (as Clay said). Let me see if I can summarize:

* User accesses own account, gets swift_owner and swift_writer set in the env.
* User accesses another account, gets swift_writer set if write functionality is enabled, no matter what the request was for

So the swift_writer is needed because it distinguishes access by accounts that can write in the accounts but aren't "owners"? This seems like extra complexity that I wouldn't imagine is required. Do you have a use case, or did you include it for completeness? I guess my confusion is why we need to treat the "owner" of an account differently than someone with full write permissions.

If you remove the concept of swift_writer, then you also don't need the extra account_write_acl. You can mirror the container-level ACLs and simplify the auth contract.

Granted, since the auth system is pluggable, any one of them could choose to implement things this way or not. But since tempauth is seen as the model to follow, I'd prefer to stay as simple as possible.

I'd also like to echo Clay's comments about using get_info() to set the acl data.'}, {'account_id': 4108, 'date': '2013-08-09 09:10:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 21:

Its been a while since we were working on that, and the vacation did not help, but let me try to recap the reasoning for Swift_writer: Swift_writer is used in  swift/proxy/controllers/container.py line 74. This is not my first choice either and maybe we can find better ways to do the filtering in the future (we tried during this patch but it opened up its own case of worms). As discussed with Clay, if user X is not owner of the account, she may still be able to read/create/list containers if the Account ACLs are set. Now if X has read access to the account but no write access to the account, swift should prevent X from reading certain container metadata such as the container_sync keys – otherwise X can read the keys and use them for writing to the container in a different cluster. 

Get_info is being used to get the account ACLs already (see swift/proxy/controllers/container.py line 60). My understanding of Clay's comment is that we may also use account ACLs to control the access to objects… This is an interesting direction, but it is yet another extension to the ACLs  - beyond the one suggested here. Once someone comes up with a full plan how account ACLs affects object access and how they co-play with container ACLs (e.g. should I have access on both to access an object?) we may consider it."}, {'account_id': 4108, 'date': '2013-08-18 06:12:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21: (5 inline comments)

Nothing happening with this patch and its getting older and less likely to merge without resolving additional conflicts that arer being added with other merges. 

I had another look at the comments and noticed there where some that I did not respond to.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-09-09 23:37:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21:

The code seems to do what it sets out to do... but that objective seems odd to me. It looks like account ACLs don't affect object requests, just container ones.

For example, if I set "X-Account-Read: .r:*" on my account, that lets anybody get a listing of any of my containers, but they can't read the objects in those containers.

What I would expect is that the objects would be readable unless I set a container ACL, in which case we'd pay attention to that instead. So, an object GET honors the container ACL unless there isn't one, in which case it honors the account ACL unless there isn't one, in which case it checks my ownership of the object and decides that way.

It's just my opinion, but I don't care about giving people access to my container listings. I really only care about objects.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-09-18 18:25:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 21: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(just reifying my opinion for Gerrit; see previous review for explanations)"}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-26 06:03:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21: Abandoned

GET/HEAD object provides:
- req.acl = container read_acl (reading)

PUT/POST/DELETE objects provides:
- req.acl = container write_acl (writing)

GET/HEAD container provides
- req.acl = account read_acl (listing)
- req.account_acl = account read_acl (reading)

PUT/POST/DELETE container provides
- req.account_acl = account write_acl (writing)

GET/HEAD account provides
- req.account_acl = account read_acl (listing)

As before, it is upto the authorization system to decide which acl
to use and how.

delay_denail was added to container PUT/POST/DELETE

tests were added to ensure appropriate acls are sent

commit_message:
Account ACLs

Add support for optional account ACLs:

The authorization API is extended to include:
container acls (as before) and account acls (new)

tempauth was updated to demonstrate the change:
  account admins can use  X-Account-Read and X-Account-Write to set
  Accounts ACLs. In this way account admins can grant other users
  the ability to create/list/delete containers.

Documentation was updated to descibe the optional new support.

As before, it is upto the authorization system to decide which ACL
to use and how.

delay_denial was added to account GET/HEAD
delay_denial was added to container PUT/POST/DELETE

tests were added to ensure appropriate acls are sent

DocImpact

Blueprint: account-acls

Change-Id: I0c31049c0842945cfe9ed26b2f54a99ecbfa70b3

commit_message:
Add MVRP support to LinuxBridge plugin

Enabled in /etc/neutron/plugins/linuxbridge/linuxbridge_conf.ini:

    [agent]
    mvrp = True

LinuxBridge will issue commands to configure network interfaces with
MVRP enabled, like so:

    ip link add link eth1 name eth1.100 type vlan id 100 mvrp on

Requies linux >= 3.9.8, and iproute2.  See contrib/mvrp/README.rst for details.

Implements: blueprint mvrp-linuxbridge
Change-Id: Ib0efeafca53dc801187c0655aa03244a6e5949f7

[{'created': '2013-09-18 18:56:02.000000000', 'message': 'Add support of setUp and tearDown for test scenarios

Scenarios are based on pytest.
We run specified tests M times using N pytests in N threads.
So we are not able to make setUp and tearDown for all pytests
only one time.

So we are adding 2 new decorators to be able to bind to any of

commit_message:
Add support of setUp and tearDown for test scenarios

Scenarios are based on pytest.
We run specified tests M times using N pytests in N threads.
So we are not able to make setUp and tearDown for all pytests
only one time.

So we are adding 2 new decorators to be able to bind to any of
test scneario functions that will be called before and after test
scnearion.

blueprint test-engine-utils

Change-Id: I4a5d02f48b2d0d22fbaf2b04c9af353184046bcb

commit_message:
Fix problem specifying VMware network name in flat networking

In FlatNetworking mode, VMware driver uses flat_network_bridge
parameter to look for or create networks in the ESX host. Because
flat_network_bridge is used by Network Manager to create linux
bridge, the network name should be a valid bridge identifier.

The fix uses vmware.integration_bridge instead of flat_network_
bridge for the network_name.

Fixes: bug #1226425

Change-Id: I54373e00440e36fce920a1a5f613ff571a63ff91

commit_message:
Reworked cli and mcli to use argparse

THIS IS A WORK IN PROGRESS, but I invite comments.
- Optparse changed out in favor of argparse
- CliOptions removed; APIToken created to manipulate that
- Removed _require and params fields in anything descended from CommandsBase

- Tox tests not attempted, as coverage has been destroyed
- Small glitch when missing required args for an action are missing: usage is printed once before __doc__  and once after
- Verbose and Debug in _pretty_print to be revisited for empty and error cases, OK printed almost without fail

The goal here is to make it much easier to follow and maintain these commands, especially the authentication process.

Change-Id: I8b89cd066af3f96f9b2ece559ea97e05a54f578a

commit_message:
change git show to | head -1

git show uses default system pager, which for people that have
funky pagers, goes sideways. Pipe this through head -1 to ensure
we only get the single change line we care about.

Change-Id: Iff22612b555bf58fe12101701cfe593f37e8f8de

When an user updates project ID, it is necessary to make sure
the new tenant is available.

Remove the member role from the old tenant.

Add the member role to the new tenant.

Fixes bug 1201251

Change-Id: Ic6704b4007d7981d73ab760c88eb5145c2b988c6
'}]
commit_message:
Add user to project if project ID is changed

When an user updates project ID, it is necessary to make sure
the new tenant is available.

Remove the member role from the old tenant.

Add the member role to the new tenant.

Fixes bug 1201251

Change-Id: Ic6704b4007d7981d73ab760c88eb5145c2b988c6

commit_message:
Change pyrax identity_type of Rackspace resources

The Rackspace resources utilize the pyrax library. As of v1.4.11 of
pyrax, the manner in which default region is determined changed, such
that the keystone identity_type returned 'RegionOne' as the default
region rather than one of the Rackspace regions. Changing the
identity_type to rackspace fixes this.

Closes-Bug: 1227387
Change-Id: I193be7d81e83a42e33a7598d665e9d1970f10e9b

commit_message:
Move tests/unit/storage/base under m/tests/storage

If we want third-party backends to inherit from these tests, we need to
ship them along with Marconi. This patch moves storage base tests under
marconi/tests/sotrage.

Implements blueprint refactor-system-tests

Change-Id: Ic7390ead37694bdac9eb341da6f239b8c1178e1e

This patch brings together oslo.cache, oslo.config, and stevedore to
provide pluggable, hierarchical catalogue caching for marconi proxy.

Here's the list of changes:
- add configuration/driver loading at the app level
- remove select from proxy storage driver - unnecessary intelligence
  at storage layer
- node.weighted_select -> partition.weighted_select (clearer name)
- forwarding logic further refactored, placed in own module
- caching logic placed in lookup module
- selector passed down at app level to handle round-robin state
  globally
    * open to becoming configurable
- adds several TODOs for a better proxy

commit_message:
proxy: adds oslo.cache, config support, & stevedore

This patch brings together oslo.cache, oslo.config, and stevedore to
provide pluggable, hierarchical catalogue caching for marconi proxy.

Here's the list of changes:
- add configuration/driver loading at the app level
- remove select from proxy storage driver - unnecessary intelligence
  at storage layer
- node.weighted_select -> partition.weighted_select (clearer name)
- forwarding logic further refactored, placed in own module
- caching logic placed in lookup module
- selector passed down at app level to handle round-robin state
  globally
    * open to becoming configurable
- adds several TODOs for a better proxy

Change-Id: I3bc568315e685486d63cdce3ec278c89e3f2b2bc
Implements: blueprint placement-service

commit_message:
Stop HTTPClient from calling self.auth_token()

self.auth_token is a string, not a method, and so it shouldn't be
invoked.

Change-Id: Iad5da176fd5c7ea05f16a29c83eb718fc900607c

commit_message:
Fix wrong ppa for ubuntu 12.04

ch_installnetworking.xml introduces havana guide but uses Grizzly
ppa, which may cause critical problem in the next steps.

Fixes-Bug: #1230331

corrects that by passing the correct arguments and keyword arguments to

commit_message:
Pass correct args to vol_rpc create_volume calls

In the chance and simple scheduler, create volume was originally using
snapshot_id and image_id for request_spec and filter_properties. This
corrects that by passing the correct arguments and keyword arguments to
create_volume.

Change-Id: Icbcfbfb28f36e1f75519bf5ad6fcbcc12a9b4ec1
Closes-Bug: #1212710

commit_message:
Fix internal swift.source tracking.

In 1.8.0 (Grizzly), your proxy logs would indicate which middleware
was responsible for an internal request, e.g. TU for tempurl or BD for
bulk delete. At some point, those all turned into GET_INFO, which does
not give you any idea which specific middleware was responsible, only
that it came from a get_account_info/get_container_info call.

This commit puts it back to how it was in 1.8.0. Also, the
new-since-1.8.0 function get_object_info() got swift_source plumbing
added to it, so source tracking for the quota middlewares'
get_object_info() calls will happen now too.

Note that due to the new-since-1.8.0 in-environment caching of
account/container info, you may not see as many lines in the proxy log
as you would with 1.8.0. This is because there are actually fewer
internal requests being made.

Change-Id: I2b2ff7823c612dc7ed7f268da979c4500bbbe911

commit_message:
Cache cleaner wrongly deletes cache for non invalid images

Based on current implement of method delete_stalled_files,
it's just deleting all the images located in /incomplete
instead of using the param 'older_than' to check if it
should be deleted. So this fix will use 'older_than' to
confirm brfore deleting.

Fixes bug 1228256

Change-Id: Ica27915f8b9b098ecae1e38c8e678d6acf4f2f76

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-24 20:52:22.000000000', 'message': 'Don't insert "Any Availaibility Zone" on single-AZ configurations

In cases where there is one AZ configured, Horizon displays the
option "Any Availability Zone" as the default.  This is confusing,
since there is only one.

Since there is logic to handle the "zero AZs configured" case
already, this is in fact an off-by-one error.  Alter the logic to
also handle the "one AZ configured" case and leave the single valid
option selected.

Fixes bug: 1229935

Change-Id: I49319e9c309c1ed41fd55e9297b0b461d17c726d
'}]
commit_message:
Don't insert "Any Availaibility Zone" on single-AZ configurations

In cases where there is one AZ configured, Horizon displays the
option "Any Availability Zone" as the default.  This is confusing,
since there is only one.

Since there is logic to handle the "zero AZs configured" case
already, this is in fact an off-by-one error.  Alter the logic to
also handle the "one AZ configured" case and leave the single valid
option selected.

Fixes bug: 1229935

Change-Id: I49319e9c309c1ed41fd55e9297b0b461d17c726d

commit_message:
Adds setting for allocation rates

Nova Scheduler Filter restricts making virtual machines by physical
machine specs.(RAM)
In some cases someone hopes making many virtual machines unboundedly.
One way is setting allocation rates.

This patche provides way of setting it by use of localrc.

Change-Id: I8ec19803a8409317a9bc2c8964a0fa27aeabcac1

commit_message:
Remove unused _instance_update() method in compute api

The _instance_update() method was previously used in lock/unlock
but that changed when they were converted to use instance objects.

Change-Id: I1f1e00b31792fd13a5b72a15c0cb11cfde75f794

commit_message:
v3 API samples for servers

Adds the rest of API samples for the core servers plugin. This is separate
from the other servers api samples because the output is potentially
dependent on all the other extensions and I'm expecting lots of merge
issues.

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-specification
Partially implements blueprint v3-api-unittests

Change-Id: Iffc814f327b0047c3510bfe5b8bbcb9e0e4540db
