[{'created': '2013-09-23 05:00:29.000000000', 'message': "Determine security group API dynamically

This commit removes enable_security_group from local_settings.py
and determines which security group API should be used (nova or
neutron).

Closes-Bug: #1227804

As described in bug 1203413, there is a case where Nova security group
with Neutron driver causes a problem. The type of 'name' attribute in
add_security_group_to_instance and remove_security_group_from_instance
depends on the backend, integer for nova security group driver and
UUID for quantum security group driver to make it work as expected.

enable_security_group config parameter produces a situation where
Nova security group with Neutron driver. We can avoid this situation
by removing this parameter when using Horizon.

Change-Id: I713c6ad166e142929f0a708e93a8fedb0de48640
"}]
commit_message:
Determine security group API dynamically

This commit removes enable_security_group from local_settings.py
and determines which security group API should be used (nova or
neutron).

Closes-Bug: #1227804

As described in bug 1203413, there is a case where Nova security group
with Neutron driver causes a problem. The type of 'name' attribute in
add_security_group_to_instance and remove_security_group_from_instance
depends on the backend, integer for nova security group driver and
UUID for quantum security group driver to make it work as expected.

enable_security_group config parameter produces a situation where
Nova security group with Neutron driver. We can avoid this situation
by removing this parameter when using Horizon.

Change-Id: I713c6ad166e142929f0a708e93a8fedb0de48640

commit_message:
Remove colon in item names in LBaaS detail page

Also changes the followings for consistency with other pages:
- Replace "Tenant ID" with "Project ID"
- Show '-' when name or description is empty
- Apply yesno filter for True/False field
- Rearrange field order in pool and VIP details

Change-Id: I82a533cee61dee148aac8872868effd78e46cc45
Closes-Bug: #1230057

[{'created': '2013-09-24 22:36:45.000000000', 'message': 'make _user_to_credentials() work with v2 users

The _user_to_credentials() method in policy.py expects users to be
v3-style.  Since v2 is still supported, make it stop exploding when
fed v2 users.

Fixes Bug: 1229980

Change-Id: Iddf56a48f684ce78bc69dd84fba39a3b3c1045ea
'}]
commit_message:
make _user_to_credentials() work with v2 users

The _user_to_credentials() method in policy.py expects users to be
v3-style.  Since v2 is still supported, make it stop exploding when
fed v2 users.

Fixes Bug: 1229980

Change-Id: Iddf56a48f684ce78bc69dd84fba39a3b3c1045ea

subject: Pin hacking>=0.7.2,<0.8 in global-requirements
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 2, 'name': 'Monty Taylor', 'email': 'mordred@inaugust.com', 'username': 'mordred'}, {'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 1849, 'name': 'Joe Gordon', 'email': 'joe.gordon0@gmail.com', 'username': 'jogo'}, {'_account_id': 4146, 'name': 'Clark Boylan', 'email': 'cboylan@sapwetik.org', 'username': 'cboylan'}, {'_account_id': 5545, 'name': 'matthew wagoner', 'email': 'zxkuqyb@gmail.com', 'username': 'zxkuqyb'}, {'_account_id': 6786, 'name': 'Sergey Lukjanov', 'email': 'me@slukjanov.name', 'username': 'slukjanov'}, {'_account_id': 6873, 'name': 'Matt Riedemann', 'email': 'mriedem.os@gmail.com', 'username': 'mriedem'}]
messages:
[{'account_id': 6786, 'date': '2013-09-25 19:18:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 5545, 'date': '2013-09-25 19:22:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 4146, 'date': '2013-09-25 19:48:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Changing the requirement does not fix the problem of stale virtual environments. Tox and run_tests.sh will not update a preexisting virtualenv (by default at least). Enforcing hacking 0.7.2 doesn't hurt anything but it won't help resolve the problem either, so this is a light -1. Instead I think we need to rely on education and possibly encouragement of using `tox -re$VENV`, but this is slow."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-09-25 19:52:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Clark, ok, I get that.  To give some more detail, the problem I hit is we have an internal pip mirror and it didn't have hacking 0.7.2 (latest it had was 0.7.0).  We have some jenkins automation that is pulling the latest code from master and running 'tox --recreate -e py27,pep' against it and would keep failing in the flake8 hacking checks.  Until I compared the versions on my local workspace against what was in our jenkins slave I didn't know that hacking was backlevel in the mirror. If the version of hacking that is needed was actually in test-requirements.txt in nova, we would have failed in a more understandable way (pip won't be able to resolve the hacking-0.7.2 package in our mirror)."}, {'account_id': 4146, 'date': '2013-09-25 20:02:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I still think we have half a solution here. This change allows the upper bound of <0.8 potentially allowing this to happen again when 0.7.3 releases and so on. Setting a lower bound fixes the problem described today but not tomorrow.

Typically ranges of versions shouldn't be problematic as long as their APIs etc don't change. But hacking is special because it is used directly to check and gate our code. Probably worth seeing that mordred and jog0 have to say about this."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-25 20:49:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- gate-requirements-install http://logs.openstack.org/28/48328/1/check/gate-requirements-install/0c1ed42 : SUCCESS in 8m 53s
- gate-requirements-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/28/48328/1/check/gate-requirements-pep8/4310975 : SUCCESS in 26s
- gate-requirements-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/28/48328/1/check/gate-requirements-python27/399cb67 : SUCCESS in 1m 08s
- gate-requirements-pypy http://logs.openstack.org/28/48328/1/check/gate-requirements-pypy/4c3d03a : SUCCESS in 3m 14s
- gate-tempest-devstack-vm-full http://logs.openstack.org/28/48328/1/check/gate-tempest-devstack-vm-full/cb9eb47 : SUCCESS in 30m 18s
- gate-tempest-devstack-vm-postgres-full http://logs.openstack.org/28/48328/1/check/gate-tempest-devstack-vm-postgres-full/b4b694f : SUCCESS in 28m 34s
- gate-tempest-devstack-vm-neutron http://logs.openstack.org/28/48328/1/check/gate-tempest-devstack-vm-neutron/a2bbe07 : SUCCESS in 20m 27s
- gate-tempest-devstack-vm-large-ops http://logs.openstack.org/28/48328/1/check/gate-tempest-devstack-vm-large-ops/e1536bc : SUCCESS in 12m 57s (non-voting)
- gate-grenade-devstack-vm http://logs.openstack.org/28/48328/1/check/gate-grenade-devstack-vm/5a03a5d : SUCCESS in 24m 09s
- gate-swift-devstack-vm-functional http://logs.openstack.org/28/48328/1/check/gate-swift-devstack-vm-functional/1397a7a : SUCCESS in 12m 15s
'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-09-25 21:04:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

So all of these bugs are pointing to a different problem: there appears to be a regression in hacking 0.7.2 around the allownoqa wrapper that made some of the checks not run.  This wasn't caught because most of the tests we have are docstring tests inside of functions.

So the proper solution for this is to: fix hacking then cut a 0.8 release of hacking."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-09-25 21:25:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

In general the hacking's version model means that in a maintenance release (z in x.y.z) can only make the rules less stringent not more.

So its possible to have valid cases where a stale venv will result in this."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-09-25 21:46:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Joe/Clark, thanks for the input on this, I'm convinced this isn't a solution."}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-25 19:17:12.000000000', 'message': 'Pin hacking>=0.7.2,<0.8 in global-requirements

There have been several bugs reported in nova lately for flake8 errors
but they are only showing up if you run against the latest hacking
version. For those with a stale virtual environment or pip mirror, these
can sneak by due to the older version of hacking required in
global-requirements.

Closes-Bug: #1230277
Related-Bug: #1227655
Related-Bug: #1229753

Change-Id: Idf3da7d8982a08b69ae1f18e1d2565358f9ba075
'}]
commit_message:
Pin hacking>=0.7.2,<0.8 in global-requirements

There have been several bugs reported in nova lately for flake8 errors
but they are only showing up if you run against the latest hacking
version. For those with a stale virtual environment or pip mirror, these
can sneak by due to the older version of hacking required in
global-requirements.

Closes-Bug: #1230277
Related-Bug: #1227655
Related-Bug: #1229753

Change-Id: Idf3da7d8982a08b69ae1f18e1d2565358f9ba075

commit_message:
Support glance client can get ipv6 image url correctly

This patch is for fix bug 1208784. In openstack ipv6 environment,
if the os image url is not provided, need use the provided host
to generate literal ipv6 image url.

Fixes bug 1208784

Change-Id: Icb71241a639db02d079348f086bd7bd5f0412609

commit_message:
Sync gettextutils from oslo

Add type check for Message params when setting locale to avoid
AttributeError.

Fixes bug: #1229364

The initial change only addressed the xml aspect of the bug
and ignored the json tests.

This change updates the check to catch the same errors when

Both of these patches are temporary and after the Cinder update
lands should be replaced with a proper/strictly enforced check of

commit_message:
Fix json version of bootable check

This is a follow up to change id:
  I8a4b1f4ce3a6a420e8152ea8c66a9b3fc127fe96

The initial change only addressed the xml aspect of the bug
and ignored the json tests.

This change updates the check to catch the same errors when
performing the json version of the checks.

Both of these patches are temporary and after the Cinder update
lands should be replaced with a proper/strictly enforced check of
'true' and 'false' values in the volume['bootable'] field.

Change-Id: Iffe5d380410f5c698018a5c3106c99af05f0b80d

commit_message:
Update man pages

Updates the man pages based on the latest oslo.config and
Keystone code. oslo.config is version 1.2.0.

To generate the man pages, ran

 tools/with_venv.sh bin/keystone-all -h

and copied the output to the man page. A couple of changes were
required because of the output formatting.
1) Escape * in *.config otherwise it's considered emphasis without
   end.
2) --log-file is split to separate lines which results in a space
   in the output, so put it back together.

Change-Id: Ic76b7eafd04551ec01a3c117b9d5a73471b1e4ce

commit_message:
Update OpenStack services to support qpidd element

Configuration files are changed so that qpid is used as the rpc_backend
instead of kombu (rabbitmq) if it is specified in the metadata.

Add qpid-python to Heat, Neutron, and Cinder requirements.txt file.
These elements install using venv and don't use the system installed
libraries. These changes can be removed if requirements.txt is changed
upstream. There are two bugs tracking these changes:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/heat/+bug/1225191
https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1225232

Change-Id: I9bf6ab9d3bae668e592af65b5c8075a487e07261

commit_message:
Add setup-passwords script.

The script is run once from devtest and writes out a file
(tripleo-passwords by default) that you source into your shell
environment to set the password environment variables.  If you lose
your shell accidentally, you can source the file again later.

Change-Id: I6317d4d66a95e181d4b7e8893e6502cc07c62026

commit_message:
API GET to return only minimal data

Requests to list top-level resources like nodes, chassis or ports will
now return only a subset of it's attributes, a subresource called /detail
could be used to get the full details of the resource. This changes
is supposed to improve performance and UX, also, others OpenStack APIs
already do it the same way so it's also about being consistent between
other APIs.

Change-Id: Ida45febf60e44d50e506f3680ab371e1027010c4
Closes-Bug: #1227431

commit_message:
Fix port deletion in NEC Plugin

Cascade on delete from ports.id to packetfitlers.in_port is added
to ensure packet filter entries associated with a port.
Also joined query of packetfilter with port query is added
to avoid additional packetfilter query by port_id.

Fixes: bug #1212102

Change-Id: I8a67649f3361480eda6377b1d8a30bebd18aa714

commit_message:
Correct deleted_at value in notification messages

The deleted_at value in notification messages is currently
set from the terminated_at value in the instance record.

A comment in the code says this is to avoid confusion between
terminated_at and deleted_at,  but swapping the names doesn't
seem to be a great way to address that.

In practice "terminated and not deleted" is a transient state
unless an error occurs, and the time gap is very short.  But
deleted_at is always set when the entry is deleted in the DB,
whereas terminated_at can be left unset in some error cases.

Rather than present terminated_at as the deleted_at value in
the message we include both and let the recipient decide which
they want to use.

Fixes bug: 1227080

Change-Id: Ic67f66b6c64be1a8f43f4fdd5b1fac25f1414247

commit_message:
Clean up automated changes to requirements

Some of us like to reuse sandboxes, and keep them up to date.  This
is very difficult to do if devstack leaves modifications to
requirements.txt files after a run, since 'git pull' may refuse to
overwrite those changes.

This modification has devstack undo the changes to the requirements
files, to leave the sandbox in a clean state again.

Change-Id: Ia2d928ade8141b59b56a2c4548d760bf6911a3e5

commit_message:
tests: fix places check for timestamp equality

It's actually up to the microsecond, and not finer, so the default
places value of 7 isn't good enough.

Change-Id: Ic0438db4c9039a904a43547d5c5181400a84d22f
Closes-Bug: #1230099

'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-09-22 05:09:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(2 inline comments)

James, thanks for working on testing for tripleo. I am a little puzzled why tempest isn't the place to do this testing though. Most, if not all, of the basic assumptions being made can be set in tempest's configuration, and we will need to run tempest in some capacity against all of the tripleO clouds anyway."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2013-09-23 11:14:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I took a closer look at Tempest.  I agree we should get these tests running against TripleO.  I would still like to see some tests that are specific to what gets done in devtest though.  For instance, Tempest tests loading and listing images from Glance, but I'd like to see specific tests for listing the images we expect...is there an image called undercloud, is it in the right format, etc.  That could expose problems and things that went wrong in devtest.

I could change this patch up to be Tempest configuration files and whatever else may be needed to run Tempest.  And then also include additional tests like I had in mind, but reusing as much as code from Tempest as possible.  It looks like there is a fair amount of code that we could reuse there, base test classes, test client classes, etc.  That way, it would fit well running along side the tests from Tempest proper.

What do you think about this approach?"}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2013-09-23 18:23:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Tempest definitely seems like the right place for this sort of testing. /2 cents'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-09-23 18:32:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Right there are a few details of devtest that won't be tested directly by tempest. However, I'm not sure that testing implementation details like the names of the images in a functional test suite is actually desirable.

If we end up with a working seed, undercloud, and overcloud according to tempest, I think we can assert that any change did not regress functionality. If we fill in the holes in tempest that pertain to us, that will just strengthen all of OpenStack's functional testing.

Now, if we want unit tests to aid in diagnosing complex changes, I think those need to be narrow in focus, testing smaller pieces of code and focusing on clearly defined interfaces. Otherwise I'm afraid they will just serve to reinforce long chains of implementation details and be harder to understand."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2013-09-25 16:49:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sounds reasonable.  Instead of refocusing this review to be Tempest specific, I'll just abandon this one and submit a new review in the future for Tempest configuration, etc.  That might even be something that is better for TOCI anyway."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2013-09-25 16:49:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-21 16:06:28.000000000', 'message': "Functional test suite for devtest.

This commit adds a test suite that can be run against the OpenStack
environments that are set up by devtest.  There are tests for the
seed, undercloud, and overcloud.  The test suite could be run at the
end of a devtest run, or at various points along the process to test
progress (e.g., run tests in test_seed.py after setting up the seed).

The tests are useful to make sure that things were set up correctly
and how devtest expects.  Granted, if you get to the very end of
devtest, it's likely everything worked.  But, they also add value in
that they can be used to troubleshoot what went wrong if a devtest
step fails unexpectedly.  For example, a test that verified the nova
baremetal flavor was created as we expect, might uncover a bug if the
flavor wasn't set up correctly by Nova.

We could also have TOCI execute the tests at the end of a run.

For now, there are just a few tests to illustrate how this might work.
More tests could be added for things like:
 - verifying neutron was set up correctly
 - verifying nova was set up correctly (flavors, nodes created, etc)
 - shelling out to virsh to verify baremetal{0-2} were setup
 - basically, we could test anything that devtest does.

Change-Id: I71e0276146e5270556d1aeea457f77de31cc0c12
"}]
commit_message:
Functional test suite for devtest.

This commit adds a test suite that can be run against the OpenStack
environments that are set up by devtest.  There are tests for the
seed, undercloud, and overcloud.  The test suite could be run at the
end of a devtest run, or at various points along the process to test
progress (e.g., run tests in test_seed.py after setting up the seed).

The tests are useful to make sure that things were set up correctly
and how devtest expects.  Granted, if you get to the very end of
devtest, it's likely everything worked.  But, they also add value in
that they can be used to troubleshoot what went wrong if a devtest
step fails unexpectedly.  For example, a test that verified the nova
baremetal flavor was created as we expect, might uncover a bug if the
flavor wasn't set up correctly by Nova.

We could also have TOCI execute the tests at the end of a run.

For now, there are just a few tests to illustrate how this might work.
More tests could be added for things like:
 - verifying neutron was set up correctly
 - verifying nova was set up correctly (flavors, nodes created, etc)
 - shelling out to virsh to verify baremetal{0-2} were setup
 - basically, we could test anything that devtest does.

Change-Id: I71e0276146e5270556d1aeea457f77de31cc0c12

commit_message:
Log message for image object not found in swift

The get method of the swift driver needs logging when the image
is not found in the container.
This change also adds the location of the image to the message.

Fixes bug 1227786

Change-Id: I33bd5ee5edf985211139d9d4519b494b2b19b5a9

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-15 17:35:34.000000000', 'message': "Add log_additional_locale config property for easy log translation

Just like it is possible to configure a log file by specifying the
log_file property in the {service}.conf file, allow the secondary locale
log to be configurable via a simple {service}.conf property.

This should allow setting up the secondary locale log relatively easy
without necessarily having to create and setup a logging.conf.

For example, if nova.conf has log-file = '/var/log/nova/api.log' and
log_additional_locale='zh', the following secondary log file will be
created:

    /var/log/nova/api.log
    |------------/zh
                 |--/api.log

Change-Id: I85b4645e18277f498f7b040b7acc6d91d55245ac
"}]
commit_message:
Add log_additional_locale config property for easy log translation

Just like it is possible to configure a log file by specifying the
log_file property in the {service}.conf file, allow the secondary locale
log to be configurable via a simple {service}.conf property.

This should allow setting up the secondary locale log relatively easy
without necessarily having to create and setup a logging.conf.

For example, if nova.conf has log-file = '/var/log/nova/api.log' and
log_additional_locale='zh', the following secondary log file will be
created:

    /var/log/nova/api.log
    |------------/zh
                 |--/api.log

Change-Id: I85b4645e18277f498f7b040b7acc6d91d55245ac

commit_message:
Rebuilding stopped instance should not set terminated_at

At the end of a rebuild action, nova checks the original vm_state
of the instance to see if it was stopped. If the instance was
originality stopped, nova will stop the newly rebuild instance.
Right before the stop, nova updates the instance and sets it's
terminated_at to utcnow(). Due to this, the periodic usage audit
does not send usage for the instance.

There's no reason for setting tereminated_at here, it should only
be set as part of instance deletion

Fixes bug: 1189554

Change-Id: I141aba1b4f3c15a4c17e1fc401ae9479acafb23f

commit_message:
Fixed issue with resource OS::Neutron::Port creation

Heat was not able to create resource OS::Neutron::Port
when ip_address attr was not specified in fixed_ips property.

From Neutron point of view, attribute ip_address of property fixed_ips is
not required and can be ommited. But when specified it is should be valid
ip address.

Bug #1224472

Change-Id: I39ba545762b96fb7267c91afa5c36bd7d16be6a6

commit_message:
Add keystone backend

This patch adds keystone support for the client. It is possible to
either provide os_auth + endpoint through the CLI or all other required
params to retrieve both or one of them.

Implements blueprint keystone-integration

Change-Id: Id059d075aabb26f92c82b0a863d85743d8564f69

[{'created': '2013-09-19 08:17:40.000000000', 'message': 'Authentication API + Keystone backend

The API still needs some refactor but, the idea is to have multiple
authentication drivers that can be used depending on how Marconi was
configured.

Some things that could be change are:

    * The `authenticate` method should be request-agnostic, instead, we
      could get a target instance back from it which will then be used
      to complete the request at a transport level.

    * Avoid patching the request instance, as per above point.

Target definition is still under discussion, which is why this patch is
being submitted as-is.

Implements blueprint python-marconiclient-v1

Change-Id: I94e2c12cf0648be8557d8b2ddc43a7aa76ae313f

commit_message:
Authentication API + NoAuth backend

This patch adds a auth base class with a NoAuth backend, which is the
default auth method for Marconi.

Implements blueprint keystone-integration

Change-Id: I94e2c12cf0648be8557d8b2ddc43a7aa76ae313f

commit_message:
Added test to check list/show extensions-neutron

Added a test script 'test_extensions.py' to api/networks to verify
if list/show of extensions is successful in neutron. Also added
supporting methods 'list_extensions' and 'show_extension_details' in
network client for XML and JSON interfaces.

Implements blueprint: quantum-test-l2-abstraction

Change-Id: Ie939a3e1302060489b579baf2cd3f7023efbeb7d

commit_message:
Incorrect error code impacted by debug level

Now there are something wrong with the WSME json code,
as a result, the HTTP return code will be wrong if the
Ceilometer debug level is set as False, which is impacting
almost all the exceptions defined in wsme.exc. But it
works fine with wsme.exc.ClientSideError, so using it
before the issue is fixed by WSME.

Fixes bug 1218760

Change-Id: I842aad841bdd21c0c51f0ee0c1fc8b671fc7c85f

commit_message:
make git show not display a diff

if the top commit includes actual content, this was being displayed
in the devstack log, which was just confusing. --quiet suppresses
this.

Change-Id: Id52604d3b2b9a1372746120cb5d8d741c35576b7

commit_message:
Check policy implementation for shares api.

At this moment shares api don't check policy for
most actions. Special check policy decorator added
for necessary methods at api.py, to solve this problem.

Change-Id: I253bda9cf3219343779d62d67fd0386a7c2f3b05
Fixes: Bug#1223375

commit_message:
Fix xml response content for share list/show

For now manila list and manila show requests return
limited data for xml version. make_share method in
shares.py updated to avoid data limiting during xml
serialization.

Change-Id: I9b241f02e1bbf46f876f235df4ce052490b8aeab

commit_message:
api ec2token: Clear failure when no auth_uri specified

Currently if the CFN API is misconfigured, such that no auth_uri
is set in the config, we silently fail because we don't detect that
auth_uri==None in the code.  Instead catch this situation and assert
that the service is misconfigured via a 500 response.

Change-Id: I47a385aa6a34fe3133de00cf2b18fec6a4f6645a
Partial-Bug: #1229674

commit_message:
Improve the CM shell client alarm visualisation

This change aim to get a better alarm representation in shell.

In alarm-list:
* it add a short sentence to describe the alarm rule
* it remove project_id/user_id because it always show the same id for
  all alarm for end-user

In alarm-show, it show alarm rule attributes as alarm properties instead
of a unparsable json in the rule property.

example of short sentence for column 'Alarm condition':
* combinated states (AND) of 8babd6a2-c457-42d0-9eb5-cdfb3cb50203,
  d0e11a94-8f59-48a9-8f6d-b0d68aaac8d0
* cpu_util >= 50.0 during 1 x 60s

Change-Id: If4df2dc08f9f4cb7796fd98308c7d62e311d1138

python is used to compare reference, bootable volume is not
detected. We should use `==' to compare values instead.

commit_message:
Comparing device name values instead of their reference

Although end users specified device name as `vda' but since `is' in
python is used to compare reference, bootable volume is not
detected. We should use `==' to compare values instead.

Fixes bug #1229610

Change-Id: I7f127dc489706482f6bb245372bfd8079b91c40f

commit_message:
Replace first_public_address/first_private_address

OS::Nova::Server attributes first_public_address and first_private_address
will not work with neutron, which allows any network name to be assigned
not just 'public' and 'private'.

This change replaces these attributes with a 'first_address'
attribute which uses the same nova_utils.server_to_ipaddress method
that AWS::EC2::Instance uses to populate all of its IP address
attributes.

This needs to be fixed before the Havana release to avoid these
broken attributes needing to be supported.

Change-Id: I0b4dc009d665e4d7b4cbc32d484a2efc6068320a
Closes-Bug: #1228929

commit_message:
Add source field to Meter model

Just like Sample model, we should also add source field to
Meter model to identify where the meter comes from.

Change-Id: I2381d67f84692bfc7d167c2b0d90bfa32b845f00
Fixes: Bug #1225583

str_replace uses python templates, whereas Fn::Replace uses python
string.replace.

During the original review for Fn::Replace, python templates were
decided against because $ would often need double-escaping in shell scripts.
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/31736/

Having different behaviours between Fn::Replace and str_replace will
add complication for users migrating existing templates to HOT.

Another advantage of using straight string replacement is seen when
the template generates a executable script. In this case it is generally

format required placeholders to be prefixed with a $.

to be fixed.

commit_message:
HOT str_replace to use string.replace, not string.Template

str_replace uses python templates, whereas Fn::Replace uses python
string.replace.

During the original review for Fn::Replace, python templates were
decided against because $ would often need double-escaping in shell scripts.
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/31736/

Having different behaviours between Fn::Replace and str_replace will
add complication for users migrating existing templates to HOT.

Another advantage of using straight string replacement is seen when
the template generates a executable script. In this case it is generally
possible to write a template that can also be executed directly in a
dev/test environment. This would often not be possible if the template
format required placeholders to be prefixed with a $.

Whatever behaviour exists when Havana is release will have to be
supported indefinitely so now is the time to decide if this is going
to be fixed.

Closes-Bug: #1228640
Change-Id: I72879b374a3c61dfe0e4004251ab709d914f2e25

A little more explanation on this, I talked through it with Duncan to try and be more clear :)

Duncan pointed out that doing things like crashing the service early on a conf issue is good because it keeps us from having a boat load of failed items pile up.  On the other hand if you have multi-backend config this would crash ALL of the backends.

What I would propose is that for things like this we raise an InvalidConfiguration exception, catch those in the manager and when they're received we disable that specific back-end.

That doesn't apply to the no-size exception, I'll grant you on that one maybe just doing the re-raise is fine because something is apparantly very messed up in that case and maybe you should just stop everything at that point."}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2013-09-24 19:19:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2013-09-24 19:21:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

commit_message:
LVM volume_clear: error on unexpected inputs

Currently if a user configures
volume_clear='non_existent_volume_clearer' in cinder.conf,
the LVM driver will silently delete a volume and not wipe it.

Instead, the delete operation should fail, leaving the volume
in the 'error_deleting' state.

Also fail if the volume reference does not contain either a
'size' or 'volume_size' field.

Closes-Bug: #1225194
Change-Id: I78fec32d7d5aeaa8e2deeac43066ca5e2e26d9ca

Matt, I'm sorry I wasn't clear about the commit message problem before, this is entirely my failing.

Of course, -n is understood and part of the language. I'm not suggesting we quote documentation of every feature we make use of. I look back at the way I worded my response and I see that it could have been taken that way.

So let me restate the problem. It isn't clear why that variable must now be quoted when the author didn't believe or failed to notice that it needed to be quoted before. If this is just "best practices", so be it, that is the reason and I'll gladly accept the patch with that reason.

I really hate -1'ing this twice. I know that it is a tiny change, and I'm being a principled party pooper. It is really important to me that the reasons we're so insistent about change log content are understood and agreed upon. It isn't just bike shedding.

When we are digging for answers and something is broken, we need to be able to grok the motivations behind each change.

We can't assume image.name is a valid attribute as Glance
doesn't send it for images that don't have a name.

This is a targeted fix to handle two cases where we access the name.
Where the name is not available, this shows the ID instead.

In the future we may want to look at wrapping images in our own class

Change-Id: Ida50ce74efafff287a0189dc90aa529e80bd5961
Closes-bug: 1223921
"}]
commit_message:
Fix editing of nameless images

We can't assume image.name is a valid attribute as Glance
doesn't send it for images that don't have a name.

This is a targeted fix to handle two cases where we access the name.
Where the name is not available, this shows the ID instead.

In the future we may want to look at wrapping images in our own class
so we can clean up data as it is returned from the API.

Change-Id: Ida50ce74efafff287a0189dc90aa529e80bd5961
Closes-bug: 1223921

[{'created': '2013-09-18 07:17:07.000000000', 'message': 'Fix excessive volume_get requests in snaps table

The volume snapshots table has a column that shows the associated volume
name and links to its volume detail page. This calls volume_get twice
for each snapshot, so loading the Images & Snapshots page takes forever
if you have a decent number of snapshots.

This commit instead gets the volume list at the same time as the
volume snapshot list, and stores the volume as an attribute on
the snapshot so it can be easily retrieved later.

Closes-bug: 1218259
Change-Id: I004e50aae51a6ed7549da41967bc42babfa6cb45

commit_message:
Fix excessive volume_get requests in snaps table

The volume snapshots table has a column that shows the associated volume
name and links to its volume detail page. This calls volume_get twice
for each snapshot, so loading the Images & Snapshots page takes forever
if you have a decent number of snapshots.

This commit instead gets the volume list at the same time as the
volume snapshot list, and stores the volume as an attribute on
the snapshot so it can be easily retrieved later.

Closes-bug: 1218259
Change-Id: I004e50aae51a6ed7549da41967bc42babfa6cb45

[{'created': '2013-09-23 05:46:05.000000000', 'message': 'Allow Django unknown language in LANGUAGES settings

Language preference form expects all languages in LANGUAGES in
openstack_dashboard/settings.py. This leads to an error when
adding a language not listed in django/conf/locale to LANGUAGES list.

commit_message:
Allow Django unknown language in LANGUAGES settings

Language preference form expects all languages in LANGUAGES in
openstack_dashboard/settings.py. This leads to an error when
adding a language not listed in django/conf/locale to LANGUAGES list.

This commit allows such language to LANGUAGES in the settings file.

Closes-Bug: #1229026

Change-Id: I37d7f4b089b0299942f25084f741a557467b3be7

commit_message:
Don't send unuseful rpc alarm notification

If the alarm have no actions for the new state we don't need to send a
message through the rpc for notification, just log a debug message
when it occur.

Fixes bug 1224416

Change-Id: I9aeb01e936dbacfbabb06e8b408d5ee04a93cb34

commit_message:
Added XML serialization for access actions

Resources related to share access management hasn't xml
serrialisation so it returns incorrect response for xml
requests. XML temptates constructors added to
share_actions.py ato solve this problem

commit_message:
Colorize Neutron log output and refactor log setup code

Bug 1214616

This patch adds colors to on-screen Neutron log output in the same way nova,
cinder, and heat engine do.
To this aim, colorized logging configuration has been moved to ./functions.
The reason for this refactoring is that these instruction are the same or
very similar for each project, with the only exception of the target
configuration file.

Change-Id: Idf0d1b842bb9ab046c9ef826de1dfc55b3f1df9d

commit_message:
Check policy implementation for shares api.

At this moment shares api don't check policy for
most actions. Special check policy decorator added
for necessary methods at api.py, to solve this problem.

Change-Id: I6a11fbf5d5162ec49670103a98872d3e00e2d996
Fixes: Bug#1223375

commit_message:
fix(mongodb): Remove $or clause used to claim messages

The $or clause was removed from one of the queries in
ClaimController.create() because it is no longer necessary,
and makes the query slower than it would otherwise be.

Mongo will just use the _id_ index now, which should be fine
since scanning a small set of messages by c.e is fast.

Change-Id: Ifcb918ef66d072a10690ad49406f4a787e84becd
Implements: blueprint bp/api-perf-tuning

[{'created': '2013-09-22 09:40:25.000000000', 'message': "Do not set error_attach and error_detach states

Failing to attach or detach a volume should not affect its status (for
example, due to passing a bad parameter). Exceptions are still raised,
and the volume's state is left unchanged. This should be sufficient to
detect a failed attach/detach, without affecting future operations on
the volume due to changed status.

Fixes: bug 1223189

Change-Id: I415dec19125ae29be4ce56522733ed18c5b09382
"}]
commit_message:
Do not set error_attach and error_detach states

Failing to attach or detach a volume should not affect its status (for
example, due to passing a bad parameter). Exceptions are still raised,
and the volume's state is left unchanged. This should be sufficient to
detect a failed attach/detach, without affecting future operations on
the volume due to changed status.

Fixes: bug 1223189

Change-Id: I415dec19125ae29be4ce56522733ed18c5b09382

commit_message:
Add volume name arguments

This patch adds volume name arguments to the following subcommands:
 * snapshot-create
 * backup-create
 * backup-restore
 * transfer-create

Fixes bug #1220590

Change-Id: Ib0ff6e62d45abb14fa8c7313511ef6f72befe0d5

commit_message:
Remove version from setup_requires

setup_requires cannot effect an upgrade, but a version being listed can
block things from operating happily. Remove the version pin from
setup_requires. Also, the setup_hooks are no longer needed.

Change-Id: Idda7d67a21c9245ca8c17973e847629bd3b4e3f2

commit_message:
Add locking to test_list_hosts_with_zone

test_list_hosts_with_zone() makes 2 list_hosts calls and expects that
the hosts' availability zone will remain constant between the calls.
However when running in parallel there is no guarantee of this, and
the aggregates tests will change the compute host's availability
zone. This commit adds the 'availability_zone' to the test to ensure
it doesn't run at the same time as the tests which will change the
host's availability zone.

Fixes bug 1228225

Change-Id: I14773e38b5cc35679b16940ad230c7c81aeaad9c

commit_message:
Prevent modal forms from closing

Forbit form closing by clicking on the backdrop.
This will prevent data lost without any other actions.
It still possible to close from on the "Esc" button.

Fixes bug#1062065

Change-Id: I6be7f76a242687bedbf9185ba627a3ffbe556ab3

It looks like the new model, trove.extensions.mgmt.flavors.models.ServiceFlavor, is not really an extension as the plan is to load it when creating instances to see if the service_type for a given flavor is a match for an instance (see this pull request : https://review.openstack.org/#/c/44950/). So it's actually a new core piece of functionality. I think because of this, ServiceFlavor, and maybe FlavorManage as well, needs to be moved into trove.flavor.models.

The create feature of the MGMT API can still live in trove.extensions.mgmt.flavors.service, as maybe not everyone will use it. However, to me that also seems like core. Let's see what other people think."}, {'account_id': 739, 'date': '2013-09-10 03:41:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Do not merge

I agree completely w/ tim. This is functionality that needs to be taken out of the mgmt api and moved into core.

As for the "create" being in the mgmt api, i think it makes sense. commit_message:
Adds support for admin to create flavors through mgmt API

Extending the management API to allow for an admin to
create flavors categorized on service type in trove.

Change-Id: Iaa0c930c9d211726a8a5ffb0cca7faf03695b65d
Implements: blueprint service-type-filter-on-flavors

Overall the changes looks ok for fixing bugs. 

But, I have a suggestion for a protocol dict introduced in this change.
As per IANA protocols hold number from 0 to 255. I am sure as we progress we will introduce new protocol support in secgroup. They are unchangeable mappings as per standard and thus we should treat it like one.

Wouldnt something like following be better?
protocol_list = [(1, 'ICMP'), (2,'IGMP'), (6, 'TCP')] #list of immutable elements
proto_map = dict(protocol_list) # for O(1) search based on keys. We can have proto_name as key as well.

This will ensure that list's element remains immutable + one can access using it as dictionary for O(1) search."}, {'account_id': 107, 'date': '2013-09-04 14:05:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: Rebased'}, {'account_id': 7962, 'date': '2013-09-04 14:06:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-09-17 03:56:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(6 inline comments)

I noticed the following important concerns about this patch when I start the test. We need to clarify the the potential risks of this patch. Since we are close to the release now, we must be careful about changing the allowed values.

My concerns all come from the change in the allowed IP protocol values.

(1) This is related to iptables based security group implementation. IP protocol may be passed to the iptables based security group implementation (db/securitygroups_rpc_base.py and agent/securitygroups_rpc.py are main related components). We need to check all newly accepted "name" values do not affect the iptables secgroup implementation.

(2) This is related to Nicira plugins. The detail comment is found in neutron/plugins/nicira/common/securitygroups.py. This needs a check by VMware folks.

(3) The last one is about potential risks related to plugins who have their own security group implementation. This change allows an additional IP protocol ''name''. If their implementation does not accept such IP proto value, this leads to an unexpected error.
At least midonet pluign is a plugin of this category.


(1) is related to OSS plugin. We must check OVS and LinuxBridge plugin (it covers ML2). Ryu and NEC plugin are plugins of category (1).
(2) and (3) are specific to each plugin are needs help of plugin maintainers.'}, {'account_id': 6659, 'date': '2013-09-17 11:43:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

Sounds like the solution cannot convert to a common representation. Suggestion in-line."}, {'account_id': 107, 'date': '2013-09-17 14:22:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27:

I think this change is much larger then originally anticipated. I propose deferring this to Icehouse and creating a new bug to improve this supported_protocol support so that each driver/plugin can implement the convert_protocol method individually or at least provide a set of accepted protocol names/numbers.'}, {'account_id': 6659, 'date': '2013-09-17 14:32:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27:

Since it sounds like some need the number and some need the name, could we just store them, as is currently, but when adding a protocol check both the name and numerical value (using the mapping tables)  to see if either is already in the list?

That doesn't change usage, but guarantees no duplicates."}, {'account_id': 107, 'date': '2013-09-17 15:11:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27:

Paul, see patch 1 and 2. This was my originally proposed DB solution to avoiding duplicates but that was not accepted.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-09-17 16:30:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27:

Arvind,

Sorry, I didn't propose much suggestion and how to move forward.

What do you think about adding more protocol name support at this timing? I would like to know your preference.

One option in my mind is to convert for previously known names (tcp, udp, icmp) into name and convert others into numbers after checking if number and name are interchanged. I believe this can minimize the impact on other codes. The downside is that a user see many protocol numbers.

Another idea is to convert name into number in iptables security groups RPC layer (for a protocol whose name is not supported by iptables). The simplest way is to convert all protocols other than tcp, udp, icmp into a number. Users can see a protocol by name. The downside is that we still need to investigate plugins with non-iptables security group implementation and to change iptables secgorup RPC impl."}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-09-17 16:37:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27:

Honestly speaking, patch set 10 + allow IP protocol number [0:255] is sufficient to me for Havana. Handling a duplication between a name and a number brings a user experience.'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-25 06:03:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-25 06:03:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}]

commit_message:
Security group rules validation allows duplicate rules

This commit fixes the issue where neutron would allow duplicate security
groups rules if protocol numbers and names are interchanged.

Change-Id: Ideece7aa6b48cd2fbf37e7b704a95e56366458ea
Fixes: Bug 1215181

Hi Christopher,

Thanks for your attention, I'll make a brief description about this.

------
Firstly, the origin code of def cell_get() in /nova/cells/state.py, 
  only returns a stored cell-object, not a converted json-pairs, 
  so it can't be encoded later in amqp process,
  that means we can't describe one cell through API correctly. 
You can see the error in the linked bug report:
    http://paste.openstack.org/show/46150/

Therefore, I added def get_cell_info() function for the return-value, 
  like def get_cell_info_for_neighbors() does in state.py.

------
Secondly, base on the changes above, we also need to modify 
    the related UPDATE function.

After the modification, the value of 'existing' used in 
    def update() in /nova/api/openstack/compute/contrib/cells.py,
  will not contain the key 'transport_url'.
And consider when updating a cell, only update the specified 
    key-values, do not allow default-value(None) 
    to overwrite other key-values;
so I modified the def _normalize_cell() in cells.py.

-------
And about the modifications in /nova/db/sqlalchemy/api.py,
    plz see the detailed info here:
    http://paste.openstack.org/show/46314/


The API issue is also involved in new V3-api, so I change it together. 

-------

That's the detailed commit message. 
Wish it's helpful for you, thanks~"}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-17 06:03:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Optional dependency injection

This adds support for optional dependencies using Keystone
dependency injection.

A new decorator for classes is provided.

 @dependency.optional('optional_api_1', 'optional_api_2')

If there's a provider for the dependency, the attribute
will be set to the provider instance, otherwise the attribute
will be set to None.

This can be used in combination with required dependencies.

Related-bug: #1223524
Change-Id: I2b987f10a7bc85efab136ae9e84606e666494246

commit_message:
Fix help messages for name arguments

Users can specify the name of an instance as the argument, which are
passed through find_resource(), instead of the id.
This patch changes some help messages for explaining this behavior.

Related-Bug: #1220590

Change-Id: I9af1259af4319b82b94d7b28536def3107ec5dd5

commit_message:
Improve test coverage of stack deletion

Adding tests to cover stack deletion timeout, stack deletion
failure and also to cover check_delete_complete.

Fixes bug #1220723

Change-Id: I50dbaf37f6d95b731e8496aa90c6c6e5bcc27ab1

commit_message:
Modify oauth1 tests to use generated keystone token in a call

Expanded on a test to check roles section for returned token too,
as well as using the returned token to issue a request (create user).

Change-Id: Id3e88e98aa69c0a353ca54a3d4a29cdade34939a

commit_message:
Fix FWaaS plugin to allow one firewall per tenant

The reference implementation of the FWaaS iptables
agent/driver supports only one firewall per tenant
in Havana release. However, the FWaaS plugin will
let you create more than one firewall. This is
being fixed in this patch to not allow creating
the second firewall if a firewall already exists
for the tenant.

Change-Id: I8f1cad9791723ba919b5774a63982c204686ddfe
Closes-Bug: #1228442

commit_message:
VMware: Handles no datastores case

If the host does not have datastores mounted or is in maintenance mode
then it reports empty datastores list. Modified code to ignore such cases.

Fixes bug: 1229653

Change-Id: I8f076d7b652181988b45738664a0d549c0b5ff9b

commit_message:
Require oslo.config 1.2.0 final

Now that 1.2.0 has been released, require it rather than one of the beta
release tarballs.

is downloaded and  stored to instance dir directly when it's disabled.

Fix bug #1226450

Change-Id: I90f940de3de19a41b122e098d6788a5652287605

commit_message:
Add linked clone related unit tests for VMware Hyper

Test image file is cached when linked clone is enabled, and image file
is downloaded and  stored to instance dir directly when it's disabled.

Fix bug #1226450

Change-Id: I90f940de3de19a41b122e098d6788a5652287605

commit_message:
StackResource set requires_deferred_auth=True

The dynamic evaluation of requires_deferred_auth will not work
as the nested stack has not been created when requires_deferred_auth
is evaluated.

In some cases subclasses of StackResource could implement dynamic
evaluation but for now it is safer to assume any template with a
nested stack needs requires_deferred_auth=True

Change-Id: I4ca3804ede5c7aa2167931279e5bed84480ac454
Closes-Bug: #1229412

commit_message:
Port Cisco nexus subplugin UT to ML2 mech driver UT

Fixes bug 1227889

This fix ports the Cisco Nexus sub-plugin unit tests
(neutron/tests/unit/cisco/test_nexus_plugin.py) to the Cisco ML2 mechanism
driver. The new test script will be
neutron/tests/unit/ml2/drivers/test_cisco_nexus.py.

Test cases which will be excluded from this port:
    - Test cases involving provider networks.
    - Test cases involving add/remove router networks
since these features are not currently supported in the Cisco ML2
mechanism driver.

Change-Id: I7aed85031cf402c418089d263c7e949c4631b1eb

commit_message:
port test_absolute_limits into v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: If7329c8d9296cf498d02863a84047b46bf7f0ba9

add more test cases to improve the test code coverage #1

In this patch, the following modules test coverage improved to 100%

1. ceilometer/utils
2. ceilometer/transformer/accumulator

commit_message:
Move tests in keystoneclient

This is the suggested location for tests and is adopted by most
projects. As part of this change relative imports to package imports.

Fix all the test running and coverage code to point to the new location.

Change-Id: I01264aed14f396ab9a7242e3e72b71e1bc332675

I've refactored this to move the sub-object request and loading of the manifest's segments (if an SLO) into it's own method. I've also moved the object path check into handle_multipart_delete. This way the initial manifest may be checked, along with the prerequisites, before bulk delete is called.
Forcing the generator function to return it's first object to do this didn't feel right, and if the manifest's first segment happened to be another SLO, then those errors could have been raised - which isn't the point here.
I just want any errors with the request or with the initial manifest in the request to return an error. Any errors encountered while processing the segments within the initial manifest would be reported within the bulk delete response.
Of course, the other option is to have all prerequisites checked within the generator function. In which case the response would always be '200 OK'. But this would be a change in behavior from before the sub-SLO changes (as is not returning 404 for a missing manifest is now)."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-03 00:52:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

hm- well the code is cleaner and it is better that it reports that the submanifest got a 404 but I'm not sure I like the main change in behavior.  Now if I replace a submanifest with a regular file and try to delete the top level manifest I just get a 400 response where before it would just delete that file and not report any problems. I there a reason why you prefer the 400? I think I like it better as it is so it will go ahead and delete the file if its there and continue deleting everything else."}, {'account_id': 7937, 'date': '2013-08-06 21:59:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Well, if this were a DLO I would agree. But since it's a SLO, the segments in the manifest should not change. If a user updates a segment object, then they should update the manifest.

In fact, I would argue that each segment's ETag should be stored and verified before deleting it. When retrieving or deleting an SLO, if the final object it represents is not the same as when the manifest was last updated, I think that should be an error."}, {'account_id': 995, 'date': '2013-08-06 22:53:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

ya- i do see your point. i went back and forth about which way to do it when writing it up.  hm.  I think the basic idea was to keep with the bulk-delete logic of it trying to replicate the user generating the listings themselves by doing the multipart-manifest=get calls themselves and then sending separate deletes (with no multipart-manifest=delete params) themselves. As the code is that's close to what it does. I could be persuaded otherwise though...

I do think that the response should always be a 200.  I wanted to keep that consistent. With this patch you get a 400 if the top level is not a SLO and a 200/400 in body if a sub manifest is not valid.  Also, since you are 400ing and stopping when you run into one of these bad manifests it would be better if the error message told the user which sub-manifest screwed up- its kinda hard to tell as it is.  I'd add it into the errors list I guess.

i guess with those changes i'd be fine with this- err on the side of caution and not delete the file if its not what its expecting.  They would then have to delete that file manually (or whatever) and rerun the original multipart-manifest=delete. I should have listened to wiser voices when they told me not to do multipart-manifest=delete at all :) it was writing the delete support into swift-client that changed my mind- it was kinda a drag for a client to do..."}, {'account_id': 7937, 'date': '2013-08-07 05:35:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 7937, 'date': '2013-08-07 05:40:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Thanks David. This last change would make all responses 200, and report errors with the sub-SLO within the bulk response body while allowing the other segments to be processed. Since you're good with this, I have two other questions.

Currently, if any object bulk delete processes receives a 401, this will abort further processing. Do you want to keep that behavior?

Also, if a sub-SLO is not found, do you want to pass that error to bulk so bulk doesn't have to make the request again to determine that?
Right now, the only way I see to do this would be to use `raise HTTPNotFound(HTTPNotFound().status)` so the 'error' can be checked against that known string.
OR, 'error' could include both the code and message, so it can just check the code against HTTP_NOT_FOUND. This is probably the better answer."}, {'account_id': 7937, 'date': '2013-08-09 19:14:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 7937, 'date': '2013-08-09 19:16:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

Other than the 401 issue, this should be done."}, {'account_id': 995, 'date': '2013-08-09 19:34:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

for the 401- there were 2 concerns. I wanted to fail early in case the token expired in the middle of the request so you could try again quickly- also to prevent system abuse. On the other hand if some of the segments are in containers you don't have control over (from acls) it would be nice if those just reported 401 errors and you kept on deleting what you could. I guess the second (not what's currently there) would be better. if the top lvl 401s the you'll still get a quick response because no sub-obj were loaded and anyway 401s are quick and there's a max of 1000 errors so should be fine."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-09 20:06:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Works for me

Also, for some additional background...

One of the problems since the sub-SLO commit is that a request to delete an SLO manifest that does not exist is returning a 200 response with the following response body:

{ 'Response Status' => '400 Bad Request', 'Response Body' => 'Invalid bulk delete.', 'Number Not Found' => 0 }

So, you can't tell if you need to retry the request or if it can be ignored. This is why I was originally trying to restore the old behavior of returning a 404 response. Of course, the solution arrived at here works just as well, since the request will return a 200 response with the following:

{ 'Response Status' => '200 OK', 'Response Body' => '', 'Number Not Found' => 1 }

I'm also hoping this commit makes it to the Rackspace servers soon :)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-23 23:45:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Works for me

update SLO delete error handling

* ensure all responses are 200 OK
* report missing sub-SLO manifests or other error messages in bulk
  delete response

In the 'virEventRegisterDefaultImpl' method in fakelibvirt.py set a boolean flag to indicate it has been called. Then in the 'openAuth' method in fakelibvirt.py validate that flag."}, {'account_id': 7750, 'date': '2013-09-04 19:59:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Dan,  I believe the boolean should be set in openAuth.  Then it should be checked in virEventRegisterDefaultImpl.  If the boolean is set, an exception is raised.   This will guarantee that virEventRegisterDefaultImpl is called before openAuth is called.  However, this still won't guarantee that the calls are made in appropriate order in driver.py

In either case, I am still not sure how to write a test that will make sure the LibvirtDriver calls libvirt.virEventRegisterDefaultImpl() before libvirt.openAuth().  None of the existing tests test LibvirtDriver.init_host(). 

What am I missing here?"}, {'account_id': 7750, 'date': '2013-09-04 22:14:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 7750, 'date': '2013-09-04 22:17:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I have updated the patch and added logic to fakelibvirt.virEventRegisterDefaultImpl() that will produce a failure if that method is used after the libvirt connection is initialized. This matches the real libvirt behavior that I am attempting to fix with this patch.

At present, no existing unit test actually triggers this failure.  The tests continue to run successfully both with and without my patch.

When I wrote a test (not in this patch) that called LibvertDriver.init_host() I learned that FakeConn class was actually being used to check the version of fakelibvirt.  As a result, fakelibvirt.openAuth does not get called.  And as a result it doesn't matter in which order init_host() calls libvirt.virEventRegisterDefaultImpl'()."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-04 22:51:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

commit_message:
Moved registration of lifcycle events handler in init_host()

The callback for handling lifecycle events now gets registered
before libvirt version is checked.  This is necesary because the
callback must be registered before the first time the connection
to libvirt is used.

Closes-bug: #1220278.

Change-Id: Id3a06c497d088078b4ea678ec9dde23bf0f406d4

commit_message:
Properly synchronize status for ports deleted from backend

Ensure that the status for a port is properly synchronized even
when the port itself does not exist anymore in the backend, avoiding
raising exceptions due to missing results in the NVP query.

This patch also adjusts a comment and improves exception handling
in _nvp_get_port_id

Bug 1229331

Change-Id: Ibaa581006c994a543c1795dd3f1d50086583b953

commit_message:
Fix NetApp iscsi drivers for cinder backup

It fixes the iscsi drivers to query backend
if a lun entry is not found in the cache. Due
to the c-bak feature spawning volume drivers
separately than c-vol it caused NetApp drivers
to error out if volume was created after starting
c-bak. This patch fixes it.

Change-Id: I3570e58560408d3f7117bb1068cf530ae05521b3
Closes-Bug:#1229620

Avishay: The goal of the original change (which introduced the bug that this change fixes) was to give administrators an early warning if they forgot to install nfs-utils on their host. Without the original change, things would still work when you did things right, you'd just get more mysterious failures when you did things wrong. This change attempts to provide the same early warning, but in a more conservative way. There's still a chance of the detection not working, but now at least that case is only as bad as the original situation where you get an error message during the actual mount operation in brick, and more importantly should only happen if the admin has done something non-standard and is smart enough to figure out what went wrong."}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2013-09-18 17:55:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

I don't really buy the "we should look for mount.nfs in a list of paths so we don't a execute a non-system one that's in /var/tmp/" argument.  Sure it might mitigate that for the detection code path, but the Cinder code doesn't care what path mount.nfs is in when it runs the command to actually mount shares, so the same problem still exists.

I think you should just run mount.nfs -V as root and look for 0 return code.'}, {'account_id': 7198, 'date': '2013-09-18 19:05:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Fix check for mount.nfs helper installation

commit_message:
Allow v2 Volume API to create volume with type name

v2 API only accepts volume type ID when creating volume, while v1
API allows both volume type name and ID (volume type name is unique
in Cinder). This patch enables v2 API to accept volume type name
as create() parameter. Aslo volume type validation code block
in v1 API create() is refactored to a slimmer version.

Change-Id: I4ee98b67a0a0e98ff4d402749e12b1335d45f64d
Close-bug: 1228835

That said, the right way to fix it might be to add a specific filter in volume.filters to handle the local case (rather than add a blanket /usr/local/bin to path)

hus_cmd_local: CommandFilter, /usr/local/bin/hus_cmd, root

then make that commit a prerequisite of this (unchanged) one.'}, {'account_id': 1994, 'date': '2013-09-24 08:09:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thierry, not quite sure what you mean but I'll see what I can do."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2013-09-24 08:15:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I'll explain a bit more. Commit da00b6bc in Cinder changed etc/cinder/rootwrap.conf so that "exec_dirs" includes /usr/local/bin. They did it so that /usr/local/bin/hus_cmd can be run as root, using the "hus_cmd" filter defined in etc/cinder/rootwrap.d/volume.filters.

Your proposed merge restores the original version, so it would break that driver. You could just add /usr/local/bin again, but then every time we sync we'll have the same issue. Another way to fix the issue is to have *two* filters from hus_cmd in etc/cinder/rootwrap.d/volume.filters: one for the generic path, and a specific one allowing /usr/local/bin/hus_cmd. You can do that by adding the filter I mentioned in the previous comment at the bottom of volume.filters.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2013-09-24 08:17:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

It's probably simpler if I just propose it :) Just a sec."}, {'account_id': 1994, 'date': '2013-09-24 08:23:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2013-09-24 08:24:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Update rootwrap with code from oslo

These are all minor changes bringing cinder up to commit c03f247

c03f247 Skip hidden files while traversion rootwrap filters
3f4d1d5 Fix os.getlogin() problem with no tty
fc04531 Send rootwrap exit error message to stderr
3663010 rootwrap: improve Python 3 compatibility
28395d9 Fixes files with wrong bitmode

Change-Id: I3a37f23a2617a7c69bc4be422f3fdcab8833e498

commit_message:
Fix processutils.execute errors on Windows

d6a963e911b8456c06dceb5ee3cc88a70c08bf82

cd oslo-incubator

Fixes bug: #1209410

commit_message:
Remove exceptions.Duplicate

exceptions.Duplicate is largely unused (one fake and one use in
cloudpipe). We should replace those users with more specific
exceptions and then remove exceptions.Duplicate.

Closes-Bug: 1228953
Change-Id: I0e7b4bae5728600fb81511a05778419b3e5577df

@Dolph Mathews

I know it is necessary to add some tests to prove the change for keystoneclient.
Unfortunately, Keystoneclient do not give the permission to change the default tenantID.

[code] from : keystoneclient/v2_0/users.py

 41     def update(self, user, **kwargs):
     42         """
     43         Update user data.
     44 
     45         Supported arguments include ``name``, ``email``, and ``enabled``.
     46         """
     47         # FIXME(gabriel): "tenantId" seems to be accepted by the API but
     48         #                 fails to actually update the default tenant.
     49         params = {"user": kwargs}
     50         params['user']['id'] = base.getid(user)
     51         url = "/users/%s" % base.getid(user)
     52         return self._update(url, params, "user")

[/code]

Which means that some one must fix this bug in keystoneclient first.

So I prefer the blueprint that split this problem into another part, which is under control.

Would you agree?'}, {'account_id': 7476, 'date': '2013-09-05 03:21:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

usage: keystone user-update [--name <user-name>] [--email <email>]
                            [--enabled <true|false>]
                            <user>

Update user's name, email, and enabled status

Arguments:
  --name <user-name>    Desired new user name
  --email <email>       Desired new email address
  --enabled <true|false>
                        Enable or disable user
  <user>                Name or ID of user to update

commit_message:
Add user to project if project ID is changed

When an user updates project ID, it is necessary to make sure
the new tenant is available.

Remove the member role from the old tenant.

Add the member role to the new tenant.

Fixes bug 1201251

Change-Id: I0c2c8971039f567180fd910e959e4a1f0574034d

commit_message:
Use name property in OS::Nova::Server if set

Currently the name property is ignored if specified; the intention
was to use the name as the nova server name if specified.

This is implemented by overriding physical_resource_name
in the same way as SwiftContainer.

Change-Id: I06a6f3d69119fb470eb54930c2bd7b329cabd6c7
Closes-Bug: #1229244

commit_message:
Added mapper for update_all on snapshot_metadata

Snapshot metadata controller have action 'update_all'
but API for this not exposed for both v1 & v2

Change-Id: I4dcd8878a4ed75bd44494fd175bb66df67e54ebc
Closes-Bug: #1228066

commit_message:
Fix swift httpd on fedora

Implements a fedora equivalent of ubuntu's sites-enabled and moves
enabling of mod_wsgi to the installation period so that it doesn't have
to be handled in a platform dependant way later.

Fixes: bug 1226363
Change-Id: I85325179f1792d985b0375572abfe8c8a82fecc3

commit_message:
Type check for Message param to avoid AttributeError

Setting the locale iteratively on Messages within a Message may cause an
AttributeError when trying to set the locale on a message substitution
that is thought to be a dict() but may be anything.

Currently even the following code would be a problem:
    msg =  _('This is a message: %s') % 'Hi'

Closes-bug: #1229364

Change-Id: I6fe55ebc4eea5fef1d335ad83a84c4879f7f06f9

commit_message:
Implemented start_power_state_change In Conductor

The start_power_state_change function in the conductor manager
allows the client to turn the power on or off for a baremetal node

Change-Id: I989a2ec60d71c55d42b14e4e2d8c8cbf8ce97151

id attribute of resources is used to construct URIs for operations on them (e. g. show/delete), which are executed for a single resource. In Nova API keypairs are identified by their names (name is a unique attribute for a given tenant) rather than by ids.

So we either can use id property here pointing to the name of the keypair, or set the id attribute to be equal to the keypair name directly.

The usage of id property seems to be more clear to me (except that we shouldn't really try to overwrite it)."}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2013-09-19 15:47:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

commit_message:
Fix AttributeError in Keypair._add_details()

_add_details() method copies keypair attributes retrieved
from Nova to an instance of Keypair class. Trying to set
attribute 'id' fails with AttributeError, because Keypair
class has a read-only property 'id'.

We can safely omit setting of attribute 'id', because it's
just an implementation detail (the id of a table row in a
database), and keypairs for a given tenant are uniquely
identified using attribute 'name'.

Fixes bug 1223934

Change-Id: I1045730e47e9e6ad31fcdfbaefdad77e2f3b2c3e

commit_message:
Add debugging to ComputeCapabilitiesFilter

When ComputeCapabilitiesFilter fails to match an extra_spec its hard to
debug which requirement is missing, add a LOG.debug statement to make
life easier.

revisions: [{'created': '2013-09-12 03:58:29.000000000', 'message': 'disassociate_address response should match ec2 The current behavior of disassociate_address does not match that of what EC2 would return when calling it upon an unassociated address. In EC2 when disassociate_address is called on an unassociated address, it returns successfully as such: aabbccdd-0146-4952-bdbe-710e4fee8387 true However, when this same called is made against the OpenStack EC2 implementation, this would return a 400: InvalidInstanceID.NotFound Instance None could not be found. req-7a9b4d03-b9f5-4243-95d8-f1ccab180631 This is due to the fact that we continue to attempt disassociation despite instance_id == None. Modify this behavior to match EC2 by simply checking that instance_id is set before continuing disassociation. Else, bail early, and in either case report success. This change also modifies unit tests to account for this change. Change-Id: I17c822d70918fefa55da2ab096af5b98b87e23e7 Closes-Bug: #1224251 '}]
commit_message: disassociate_address response should match ec2 The current behavior of disassociate_address does not match that of what EC2 would return when calling it upon an unassociated address. In EC2 when disassociate_address is called on an unassociated address, it returns successfully as such: aabbccdd-0146-4952-bdbe-710e4fee8387 true However, when this same called is made against the OpenStack EC2 implementation, this would return a 400: InvalidInstanceID.NotFound Instance None could not be found. req-7a9b4d03-b9f5-4243-95d8-f1ccab180631 This is due to the fact that we continue to attempt disassociation despite instance_id == None. Modify this behavior to match EC2 by simply checking that instance_id is set before continuing disassociation. Else, bail early, and in either case report success. This change also modifies unit tests to account for this change. Change-Id: I17c822d70918fefa55da2ab096af5b98b87e23e7 Closes-Bug: #1224251

commit_message:
Enable test_create_multiple_servers test for V3 API

Now that the multiple create extension has merged we can enable
this test for the V3 API. Need to also override post_server
for the test client for the V3 API as the data return when requesting
a reservation id in the V3 API has changed

Change-Id: I7f34f1e90b872c4679b5c54fe9e4b0f4420910ab
Closes-Bug: #1206884

commit_message:
disable direct mounting of qcow2 images by default

* nova/virt/disk/api.py: Set the default for the
'resize_fs_using_block_device' option to False,
so that we don't enable this functionality because:
1. It's not needed for newer images that resize themselves.
2. It enables direct mounting of images which might otherwise
   be disabled for security reasons.
3. It's not supported on systems without the nbd module.
4. It gives noisy diagnostics on such systems.

Fixes bug: 1212734

Change-Id: Ifbd687eae46606176ea196888eeffdde08559c01

commit_message:
Revert "Update oslo.config"

This reverts commit 2b3da5e312a2ab94cf3a46183bdd4299acbb7129

We shouldn't release a version of keystoneclient to pypi which
requires a version of oslo.config which isn't on pypi.

Also, keystoneclient doesn't actually require any new
oslo.config APIs.

Change-Id: I271c2f83087c7d6e07a2e3236568935bfd3c33ae

commit_message:
service: check that timestamps are almost equals

Sometimes timestamp get rounded during conversions and fails. Let's use
assertAlmostEqual to be safe.

Change-Id: I79e935d4b54013a18d2e07e71411f2ead94d977f
Fixes-Bug: #1223346

commit_message:
Convert TestCases to NoDBTestCase

NoDBTestCase is faster because it skips initializing a database for
tests which don't actually talk to the database. Its also nicer
because its more explicit about the dependancies of a given test.

commit_message:
Make auth backend use OPENSTACK_ENDPOINT_TYPE parameter from settings.

And if parameter is missing in dashboard's settings, use default value of
'publicURL'. This default value doesn't fit documentation at
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/horizon/topics/settings.html#openstack-endpoint-type,
but as lin-hua.cheng@hp.com said (see
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/45679/) documentation should
be fixed itself.

More tests were added: same checks for V2 and V3 are also run for
three possible values of settings.OPENSTACK_ENDPOINT_TYPE ('publicURL',
'internalURL' and 'adminURL'). Old test suites correspond to
settings.OPENSTACK_ENDPOINT_TYPE parameter not being set.

Closes-bug: #1221563
Change-Id: Ic164d1cfcb0c7606c7ca51b869a738b2976bf6ea

[{'created': '2013-08-28 05:56:58.000000000', 'message': "VMwareVCDriver: Fix instance create with sparse disk image

The same approach of calling VirtualDiskManager.CopyVirtualDisk
without destination disk spec in the cluster driver for fixing 1184807
turns out to work for copying a sparse disk as well because the behavior
of vCenter's behavior for specless copy of a sparse disk is to do the
reasonable thing of converting a sparse disk to thin-provisioned, and a
flat disk to preallocated.

Tests done:

Verified using tempest that sparse/thin/preallocated image types deploys
properly through the cluster driver. Tempest output to be included in
the review comments.

Fixes bug 1171226

commit_message:
VMwareVCDriver Fix sparse disk copy error on spawn

The same approach of calling VirtualDiskManager.CopyVirtualDisk
without destination disk spec in the cluster driver for fixing 1184807
turns out to work for copying a sparse disk as well because vCenter's behavior
for specless copy is to do the reasonable thing of converting a sparse disk to
thin-provisioned, and a flat disk to preallocated.

Tests done:

Verified using tempest that sparse/thin/preallocated image types deploys
properly through the cluster driver. Tempest output to be included in
the review comments.

Fixes bug 1171226

Change-Id: I6c48866e06c2aa656c89848564f3262fb7b79039

commit_message:
Ensure any relevant tokens are revoked when a role is deleted

Add a controller class method to delete tokens for a role, along the
lines of those that exist for deleting tokens for user and project. Ensure
this is called for both the V2 and V3 delete_role APIs.

Fixes bug 1153645

Change-Id: I3c8d70eeb387a18c30df489142ea3aefc2224ae3

commit_message:
Fix V3 API server metadata XML serialization

The XML serialisation and deserialization when updating
a single server metadata item or retrieving a single server metadata
item through the V3 API is broken as the JSON format was changed
but the corresponding XML serialisation/deserialisation wasn't.

This changeset fixes this bug and adds testcases for the fixes.

Change-Id: I1bd2a729744387337f86a37dc2ff89606edce424
Closes-Bug: #1223803

[{'created': '2013-08-22 09:26:38.000000000', 'message': "Changed 'limit' to 'page_size' in image list

1. On an image list call, there is a feature to
limit the number of images, by passing in a
keyword - 'limit' as query params.
  But python-glanceclient does not understand
'limit' keywork on image list. It understands
a keyword - 'page_size' for the same intent.
  Changed to map 'limit' to 'page_size' param
while making a call to python-glanceclient in
GlanceImageService class.

2. Added a configuration 'glance_default_page_size'
defaulted to 100, to always limit image list call
made to python-glanceclient.

3. Changed StubGlanceClient.list() method to use
'page_size' keyword instead of 'limit', to make
it more accurate to python-glanceclient.

Fixes bug 1200233

Change-Id: I1c804c74c153e80bb572ec45283ebd9b6b7b41c5
"}, {'created': '2013-08-29 15:07:30.000000000', 'message': "Changed 'limit' to 'page_size' in image list

commit_message:
Added 'page_size' param to image list

Added a new query param called 'page_size' to
accepted_query_params list in image list call.
This param is passed on to glance-client which will
be used to paginate the result set.

Fixes bug 1200233

Change-Id: I1c804c74c153e80bb572ec45283ebd9b6b7b41c5

commit_message:
Sync gettextutils from oslo

Some Messages use a Message within a Message, and we were only
translating the base Message but not the Message substitution within.

Fixes bug: #1221808

Change-Id: Ic3119df23a090cfaa160c1461e955f0af55fe1cf

commit_message:
OpenStack services to support qpidd element

Configuration files are changed so that qpid is used
as the rpc_backend instead of kombu (rabbitmq) if it
is specified in the metadata.

Add qpid-python to Heat, Neutron, and Cinder
requirements.txt file. These elements install using
venv and don't use the system installed libraries.
These changes can be removed if requirements.txt is
changed upstream. There are two bugs tracking these
changes:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/heat/+bug/1225191
https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1225232

Change-Id: I241a6cd411d4ad11a79a0e2adfb8b308e343e28d
